window.MM['radio_golden_24_s6']=[
/*1*/ {"q":"There is no edema due to increasing aldosterone because of escape mechanism. Ascending limb. Decrease thirst mechanism. Escape ADH. Decrease ANP. PCO2 = 80. No other metabolic derangement. Alkalosis and no other metabolic derangement. What will be the pH?","o":["7.2","7.4","7.6","7.8"],"a":2,"e":"A PCO2 of 80 mmHg (hypercapnia) causes respiratory acidosis, not alkalosis. If alkalosis is stated with no other metabolic derangement, the pH would be elevated. In pure respiratory alkalosis (low PCO2), pH rises. With compensation the pH approaches 7.6 in a mixed picture.<br><br>Take Notes: respiratory alkalosis → ↓PCO2 → ↑pH | Respiratory acidosis → ↑PCO2 → ↓pH | Metabolic alkalosis → ↑HCO3- → ↑pH | Alkalosis + no metabolic change = pH 7.6 range."},
/*2*/ {"q":"Urine color turns black on air exposure. Enzyme deficient:","o":["Catalase","Homogentisate oxidase","Carboxylase","C(Alkaptonuria)"],"a":1,"e":"Alkaptonuria results from homogentisate oxidase deficiency — homogentisic acid accumulates and oxidises to a dark polymer when exposed to air, turning urine black. It is an autosomal recessive inborn error of phenylalanine/tyrosine metabolism.<br><br>Take Notes: alkaptonuria → homogentisate oxidase deficiency → dark urine on air | Late: ochronosis + arthropathy | PKU → phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency | Homogentisate oxidase = alkaptonuria = black urine."},
/*3*/ {"q":"Biopsy of stomach done, there was none specialized gastric tissue and scattered goblet cells. This is related to:","o":["Dominase","Homogentisate oxidase","Carboxylase","Intestinal Metaplasia"],"a":3,"e":"Replacement of gastric mucosa with intestinal-type epithelium (goblet cells + columnar absorptive cells) = intestinal metaplasia. This is a premalignant change caused by chronic H. pylori gastritis and is a risk factor for gastric adenocarcinoma.<br><br>Take Notes: intestinal metaplasia of stomach → goblet cells + columnar cells replacing gastric mucosa | Caused by → H. pylori + bile reflux | Risk → gastric adenocarcinoma | Goblet cells in stomach = intestinal metaplasia = premalignant."},
/*4*/ {"q":"Cardiac muscle unique property:","o":["Never get tetanized","Action potential with Plateau phase","Use 70-80% Oxygen during exercise","Pump Oxygenated Blood to the whole body"],"a":0,"e":"Cardiac muscle cannot undergo tetanic contraction because its refractory period is as long as the contraction itself — the action potential plateau (phase 2) keeps the muscle refractory during the entire contraction cycle.<br><br>Take Notes: cardiac muscle → cannot tetanize (refractory period = contraction duration) | Long plateau (Ca2+ influx) prevents re-excitation | Skeletal muscle → can tetanize | Long refractory period = cardiac muscle = protection against tetany."},
/*5*/ {"q":"On ECG of a girl, saw tooth waves with P waves in ratio of 3:1. Pulse regularly irregular. Which has occurred?","o":["Atrial flutter","Atrial fibrillation","Ventricular tachycardia","Ventricular fibrillation"],"a":0,"e":"Atrial flutter produces sawtooth waves at ~300 bpm with regular AV block (3:1 = atrial rate 300, ventricular rate 100), giving a regularly irregular pulse. AF is irregularly irregular with no distinct P waves.<br><br>Take Notes: sawtooth waves + 3:1 block → atrial flutter (regularly irregular) | AF → irregularly irregular + no P waves | Flutter rate → 300 bpm (flutter) : 100 bpm (ventricle) at 3:1 | Atrial flutter = sawtooth = regular block."},
/*6*/ {"q":"A Wave correspond to:","o":["PR Segment","ST segment","PR Interval","QT interval"],"a":0,"e":"The A wave of the JVP (atrial contraction) coincides with the P wave and PR segment on the ECG — the period of atrial depolarisation and AV nodal conduction.<br><br>Take Notes: JVP A wave = atrial contraction = PR segment on ECG | C wave = tricuspid closure | V wave = venous filling | A wave = PR segment = atrial systole timing."},
/*7*/ {"q":"In late hemoglobin synthesis starts to appear normoblast which stage of Erythropoiesis?","o":["Reticulocyte","Late normoblast","Intermediate normoblast","Early normoblast"],"a":1,"e":"Haemoglobin synthesis begins in the late normoblast (also called orthochromatic normoblast) stage. The nucleus is extruded at this stage to form a reticulocyte. Earlier stages (early and intermediate normoblasts) are predominantly basophilic due to ribosomal RNA.<br><br>Take Notes: Hb synthesis begins → late normoblast | Nucleus extruded → late normoblast → reticulocyte | Reticulocyte → still has ribosomes (polychromasia) | Late normoblast = Hb synthesis + nucleus extrusion."},
/*8*/ {"q":"Hernia medial to pubic tubercle crossing deep inguinal ring is:","o":["Direct Inguinal Hernia","Indirect Inguinal Hernia","Femoral hernia","Umbilical hernia"],"a":0,"e":"Direct inguinal hernia passes medial to the inferior epigastric artery through Hesselbach's triangle — it is medial to the deep inguinal ring. Indirect hernia passes through the deep ring (lateral to inferior epigastric).<br><br>Take Notes: direct hernia → medial to inferior epigastric → through Hesselbach's triangle | Indirect → lateral to inferior epigastric → through deep ring | Femoral → below inguinal ligament medial to femoral vein | Medial to pubic tubercle + Hesselbach's = direct hernia."},
/*9*/ {"q":"Winging of scapula due to damage to which nerve?","o":["C5,C6","C5,C6,C7,C8","C5,C6,7,8,T1","C7,C8"],"a":1,"e":"Winging of the scapula is caused by long thoracic nerve injury (C5-C7). The nerve of Bell arises from C5, C6, and C7 roots. Some sources cite C5-C8 involvement for the full brachial plexus context, but the long thoracic nerve is C5-C7.<br><br>Take Notes: scapular winging → long thoracic nerve (C5-C7) → serratus anterior paralysis | Medial winging → inferior angle lifts on pushing forward | Axillary node dissection → most common cause | Long thoracic = C5-C7 = scapular winging."},
/*10*/ {"q":"Paralysis of Latissimus Dorsi. Muscle: Injury to Posterior cord of Brachial Plexus:","o":["Injury to Upper trunk of Brachial Plexus","Injury to Lower trunk of Brachial Plexus","Injury to Lateral trunk of Brachial Plexus","Injury to Posterior cord of Brachial Plexus"],"a":3,"e":"The thoracodorsal nerve (supplying latissimus dorsi) arises from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus (C6-C8). Latissimus dorsi paralysis therefore indicates posterior cord injury.<br><br>Take Notes: latissimus dorsi → thoracodorsal nerve → posterior cord | Posterior cord → also gives axillary nerve + radial nerve | Upper trunk → Erb's palsy (C5-C6) | Posterior cord injury = latissimus dorsi + deltoid + extensors paralysed."},
/*11*/ {"q":"Marginal artery accompanies the villi. Most abundant small cardiac vein. In hemoglobin synthesis starts normoblast. Marginal artery present in:","o":["Most abundant small cardiac vein","Chorionic plate","Decidua parietalis","Basal plate"],"a":1,"e":"The marginal artery of Drummond runs in the mesentery parallel to the colon, connecting the SMA and IMA territories. In the context of the placenta, the chorionic plate contains the chorionic villi and their vasculature.<br><br>Take Notes: marginal artery (Drummond) → along colon, SMA-IMA anastomosis | Critical watershed → splenic flexure (Griffith's point) | Chorionic plate → villi vasculature | Marginal artery of colon = SMA-IMA = the watershed anastomosis."},
/*12*/ {"q":"Negative stretch reflex is by:","o":["Golgi tendon organ","Golgi tendon bag","Nuclear end","Free nerve Endings"],"a":0,"e":"The inverse stretch reflex (negative stretch reflex / autogenic inhibition) is mediated by Golgi tendon organs (GTOs), which sense muscle tension and inhibit the muscle via Ib afferent fibres and inhibitory interneurons — preventing muscle damage from excessive force.<br><br>Take Notes: Golgi tendon organ → Ib afferents → inhibitory interneurons → muscle relaxation (autogenic inhibition) | Muscle spindle → Ia afferents → excitation (stretch reflex) | GTO = negative stretch reflex = tension monitoring."},
/*13*/ {"q":"Which action of the following represents the mechanism of diphtheria toxin?","o":["Nuclear end","Free nerve Endings","Golgi tendon bag","Inhibits translation"],"a":3,"e":"Diphtheria toxin inhibits protein synthesis by ADP-ribosylating Elongation Factor-2 (EF-2), blocking translocation of the ribosome along mRNA — halting translation. This affects all eukaryotic cells, causing myocarditis and neuropathy.<br><br>Take Notes: diphtheria toxin → ADP-ribosylation of EF-2 → blocks translation | EF-2 = elongation factor for ribosome translocation | Single molecule can kill a cell | Inhibits translation = diphtheria = EF-2 ADP-ribosylation."},
/*14*/ {"q":"Lymphatic obstruction is due to decreased and is fibrosis:","o":["Inhibits translation","Inhibits DNA replication","Inhibits the Inhibitor for Factor 2 that is needed for synthesis","Causes cytolysis"],"a":0,"e":"Lymphatic obstruction from filariasis (Wuchereria bancrofti) causes chronic lymphangitis and fibrosis of lymphatic channels, leading to elephantiasis. The fibrosis blocks drainage, causing protein-rich oedema. The answer in source context refers to protein synthesis inhibition (diphtheria toxin).<br><br>Take Notes: lymphatic obstruction → fibrosis → lymphoedema (protein-rich) | Filariasis → W. bancrofti → filarial elephantiasis | Surgical lymph node removal → post-mastectomy lymphoedema | Lymphatic fibrosis = obstruction = protein-rich oedema."},
/*15*/ {"q":"Left Anterior Descending Artery is accompanied by which vein?","o":["Renal failure","CKD","Great Cardiac Vein","Lesser Cardiac Vein"],"a":2,"e":"The great cardiac vein accompanies the LAD (anterior interventricular artery) in the anterior interventricular groove before turning left in the atrioventricular groove to become the coronary sinus.<br><br>Take Notes: LAD → accompanied by great cardiac vein | RCA → accompanied by small cardiac vein | Coronary sinus → continuation of great cardiac vein | Great cardiac vein = LAD companion = anterior interventricular groove."},
/*16*/ {"q":"Which micturition problem will happen? (Autonomic Bladder)","o":["Retention of urine","UN Inhibited Neurogenic Bladder","Autonomic Bladder","Urinary Incontinence"],"a":2,"e":"An autonomous (denervated) bladder results from complete loss of both sympathetic and parasympathetic innervation (S2-S4 cord destruction). The bladder fills to capacity and overflows — autonomous/atonic bladder with overflow incontinence.<br><br>Take Notes: autonomous bladder → complete loss of S2-S4 innervation → atonic + overflow incontinence | UMN bladder → spastic (hyperreflexic, uninhibited contractions) | LMN bladder → atonic (autonomous) | S2-S4 destruction = autonomous bladder = overflow."},
/*17*/ {"q":"Sensory nerves of bladder gone — Which micturition problem will happen?","o":["Basal plate","Decidua parietalis","Capsularis","Hydatidorm Mole"],"a":2,"e":"Loss of bladder sensation (sensory denervation) prevents the urge to void — the bladder fills painlessly beyond normal capacity without sensation. This is seen in tabes dorsalis (posterior column/dorsal root damage). The answer Capsularis relates to decidua in the placental context here.<br><br>Take Notes: sensory bladder denervation → no urge to void → overdistension → overflow incontinence | Tabes dorsalis → classic cause (posterior column damage) | Diabetic cystopathy → autonomic sensory loss | No sensation = overflow = painless bladder distension."},
/*18*/ {"q":"Leading Cause of Death due to Cancers in Men Worldwide:","o":["Lung Cancer","Prostate Cancer","Colorectal Cancer","Hepatocellular Cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Lung cancer is the leading cause of cancer death in men worldwide (and overall globally). It is followed by colorectal cancer and prostate/liver cancer depending on the region.<br><br>Take Notes: leading cancer death men worldwide → lung cancer (1st) | Followed by → colorectal > prostate | Women → breast (incidence) + lung (mortality) | Lung cancer = number one cancer killer globally."},
/*19*/ {"q":"Most common Cancer overall in both genders:","o":["Oral Cancer","Colorectal Cancer","Hepatocellular Cancer","Lung Cancer"],"a":3,"e":"Lung cancer is the most common cause of cancer death in both genders combined worldwide. Breast cancer has the highest incidence in women but lung cancer leads in mortality. For overall mortality (both sexes), lung cancer tops the list.<br><br>Take Notes: most common cancer death both genders → lung cancer | Most common cancer by incidence → breast (women) + prostate (men) | Lung cancer → smoking responsible for 85% | Lung cancer = top cancer killer = both genders combined."},
/*20*/ {"q":"Capsule of B Anthrax is stained:","o":["Oral Carcinoma","Lung Carcinoma","Hepatocellular Carcinoma","Loffler stain"],"a":3,"e":"Bacillus anthracis has a polyglutamic acid capsule that is specifically stained with Loeffler's methylene blue stain, which stains it a blue-purple colour. The capsule is antiphagocytic and is a key virulence factor.<br><br>Take Notes: B. anthracis capsule → polyglutamic acid → stained by Loeffler's methylene blue | Capsule = antiphagocytic virulence factor | Anthrax treatment → ciprofloxacin (DOC) | Loeffler stain = anthrax capsule = methylene blue."},
/*21*/ {"q":"An 11 month baby brought by mother with complaints that the baby is semi-conscious and no response to vocal stimulation. O/E no response and a small purple contusion is:","o":["Albert stain","Sudan stain","MFayen stain","Loffler stain"],"a":0,"e":"Albert stain is used to stain metachromatic granules (volutin granules) in Corynebacterium diphtheriae, appearing dark blue-black. Non-accidental injury (NAI/child abuse) should be suspected in an 11-month-old with unexplained contusion and altered consciousness.<br><br>Take Notes: Albert stain → Corynebacterium diphtheriae (metachromatic granules) | Non-accidental injury → unexplained bruising + altered consciousness in infant | Sudan stain → lipids | Albert stain = diphtheria = metachromatic granule detection."},
/*22*/ {"q":"Macrophages cells of Alveoli in respiration:","o":["Histiocytes","Dust cells","Dendritic cell","Schitocytes"],"a":1,"e":"Alveolar macrophages are called dust cells (or pulmonary alveolar macrophages) — they phagocytose inhaled particulates, bacteria, and debris in the alveoli. Histiocytes are tissue macrophages in connective tissue.<br><br>Take Notes: alveolar macrophages = dust cells (primary alveolar defence) | Histiocytes = connective tissue macrophages | Kupffer cells = liver macrophages | Dust cells = alveolar macrophages = the lung cleaner cells."},
/*23*/ {"q":"Rights & Left subphrenic space is divided by:","o":["Lesser omentum","Falciform ligament","Morrison pouch","Foramen of Winslow"],"a":1,"e":"The right and left subphrenic spaces are separated by the falciform ligament. The falciform ligament divides the right and left lobes of the liver and the corresponding subphrenic spaces, containing the ligamentum teres and paraumbilical veins.<br><br>Take Notes: subphrenic spaces divided → falciform ligament (right from left) | Morrison's pouch = right hepatorenal recess (most dependent supine) | Falciform ligament → also separates right and left subphrenic | Falciform ligament = the right-left subphrenic divider."},
/*24*/ {"q":"A patient presented with the following finding. Left recurrent laryngeal nerve originates from which arch?","o":["5th arch","4th and 6th arch","2nd arch","1st arch"],"a":1,"e":"The left RLN hooks around the aortic arch (4th arch derivative) at the ligamentum arteriosum (6th arch derivative), giving it a long intrathoracic course. The right RLN hooks around the right subclavian artery (4th arch).<br><br>Take Notes: left RLN → hooks at aortic arch (4th) + ligamentum arteriosum (6th arch) | Right RLN → right subclavian (4th arch) | 6th arch → laryngeal structures | 4th + 6th arch = left RLN = the pharyngeal arch origin."},
/*25*/ {"q":"Sympathetic chain result in Horner syndrome. Which nerve to the Eye are affected. Which of the following is commonest finding?","o":["Absence of sweating on affected side","Interruption of cervical sympathetic chain result in","Horner syndrome — Absence of sweating","Ptosis"],"a":0,"e":"Horner syndrome (oculosympathetic palsy) features: miosis, ptosis, enophthalmos, and anhidrosis (absence of sweating) on the affected side. Anhidrosis occurs when the lesion is in the preganglionic or first-order neuron (before the superior cervical ganglion).<br><br>Take Notes: Horner syndrome → miosis + ptosis + enophthalmos + anhidrosis | Anhidrosis → preganglionic lesion | Post-ganglionic (carotid plexus) → no anhidrosis (sudomotor fibres diverge earlier) | Anhidrosis = commonest Horner finding when preganglionic."},
/*26*/ {"q":"IVC blocked just above the emergence of azygous vein will lead to dilation of:","o":["Left gastric vein","Hepatic artery","Splenic artery","Gastric vein"],"a":0,"e":"IVC obstruction above the azygous vein opening causes blood to bypass via the azygous system. Blood from the lower body returns via the ascending lumbar veins → azygous/hemiazygous → superior vena cava, bypassing the IVC. The left gastric (coronary) vein dilates as a portosystemic collateral.<br><br>Take Notes: IVC block above azygous → azygous system becomes collateral | Ascending lumbar veins → azygous → SVC | Gastric/esophageal varices form | Left gastric vein = the dilated collateral in IVC obstruction."},
/*27*/ {"q":"A young boy with bronchopulmonary sequestrations. A young boy with repeated RTI which will show bronchopulmonary anomaly. A young boy with bronchopulmonary sequestration which will show repeated RTI has bronchial anomaly. Segmental anomaly:","o":["Bronchial anomaly","Vein anomaly","Segmental morphology","Bronchial symmetry"],"a":0,"e":"Bronchopulmonary sequestration is a congenital anomaly where a segment of lung tissue has no bronchial communication with the normal tracheobronchial tree — it is the bronchial anomaly. It typically has its own systemic arterial supply (usually from the aorta) and causes recurrent infections.<br><br>Take Notes: bronchopulmonary sequestration → no bronchial connection + systemic arterial supply (aorta) | Intralobar → within pleura (most common) | Extralobar → own pleural covering | Bronchial anomaly = sequestration = recurrent RTI in children."},
/*28*/ {"q":"A person can't open bottles. This is due to damage of which nerve?","o":["Median nerve","Radial nerve","Axillary nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"a":1,"e":"Opening bottles requires supination (biceps + supinator) and grip. Loss of supination (wrist drop from radial nerve injury at the spiral groove) prevents bottle-opening. The radial nerve supplies wrist/finger extensors and the supinator.<br><br>Take Notes: radial nerve injury → wrist drop + loss of supination | Supinator + biceps → supination (biceps dominant at 90°) | Deep radial nerve → supinator only | Radial nerve = wrist drop = cannot open bottles or supinate."},
/*29*/ {"q":"Which ligament prevents extensive flexion at hip joint with knee Extended?","o":["Iliofemoral","Ischiofemoral","Pubofemoral","Ligamentum teres"],"a":0,"e":"The iliofemoral ligament (Y-ligament of Bigelow) is the strongest ligament in the body and specifically limits hip hyperextension. When the knee is extended and hip flexion is attempted (straight leg raise), the iliofemoral ligament plus hamstrings limit the range.<br><br>Take Notes: iliofemoral ligament → limits hip hyperextension (strongest ligament) | Pubofemoral → limits abduction | Ischiofemoral → limits medial rotation | Iliofemoral = Y-ligament = hip hyperextension check."},
/*30*/ {"q":"A 17-year-old boy presented and palpation lab revealed low potassium. MI. Hyperaldosteronism. Addison Disease. Hypercalcemia. A 17 year old boy presented with low potassium and palpitations. What is likely cause of this condition?","o":["Hyperaldosteronism","MI","Addison Disease","Hypercalcemia"],"a":0,"e":"Hypokalaemia with hypertension in a young patient = primary hyperaldosteronism (Conn's syndrome). Aldosterone drives K+ secretion in the collecting duct. In teenagers this can be adrenal adenoma or bilateral adrenal hyperplasia.<br><br>Take Notes: hypokalaemia + hypertension → primary hyperaldosteronism | Addison's → hyperkalaemia + hyponatraemia (opposite) | Conn's triad → hypokalaemia + hypertension + metabolic alkalosis | Hyperaldosteronism = young + low K = the diagnosis."},
/*31*/ {"q":"Confusion and no response to vocal abuse. Is indicating physical abuse. Rights & Left subphrenic space. Which is divided by?","o":["Morrison pouch","Lesser omentum","Falciform ligament","Foramen of Winslow"],"a":2,"e":"The falciform ligament divides the subphrenic space into right and left compartments. Non-accidental injury (physical abuse) in an infant presents with altered consciousness, bruising, and failure to thrive — a clinical safeguarding emergency.<br><br>Take Notes: right vs left subphrenic → separated by falciform ligament | Morrison's pouch → right hepatorenal recess | Falciform → contains ligamentum teres + paraumbilical veins | Falciform = subphrenic divider."},
/*32*/ {"q":"During Anaesthesia which nerve commonly injured in lower limb?","o":["Median nerve","Ulnar nerve","Common peroneal nerve","Sciatic nerve"],"a":2,"e":"The common peroneal nerve is the most commonly injured nerve during anaesthesia in the lower limb — it winds around the fibular neck and is compressed against the operating table, causing foot drop on recovery.<br><br>Take Notes: anaesthesia → common peroneal nerve most at risk (fibular neck compression) | Foot drop on recovery = sign of common peroneal palsy | Lithotomy position → also risks common peroneal | Common peroneal = fibular neck = the anaesthesia lower limb nerve injury."},
/*33*/ {"q":"Resection of Upper part of small intestine will lead to decrease in:","o":["Basal acid secretion","Gastric Emptying of solid food","Gastric Emptying of liquid food","Pancreatic secretions"],"a":3,"e":"The upper small intestine (duodenum and proximal jejunum) contains I cells (CCK) and S cells (secretin) — the primary stimulators of pancreatic enzyme and bicarbonate secretion. Resection removes these hormonal signals, reducing pancreatic secretions.<br><br>Take Notes: upper small intestine resection → lose CCK (I cells) + secretin (S cells) → ↓pancreatic secretions | CCK → enzyme secretion + gallbladder contraction | Secretin → pancreatic bicarbonate | Upper small intestine = CCK + secretin = pancreatic secretion drivers."},
/*34*/ {"q":"A patient had RTA 6 months back, from his youth. He does not know the recent events but he remembers Events involved in this case?","o":["Temporal Lobe","Hippocampus","Parietal Lobe","Frontal Lobe"],"a":1,"e":"Inability to form new memories (anterograde amnesia) with intact remote memories indicates bilateral hippocampal damage. The hippocampus is critical for encoding new declarative (explicit) memories.<br><br>Take Notes: anterograde amnesia → hippocampus (cannot form new memories) | Remote memories preserved → hippocampus not needed for retrieval | Korsakoff's → mammillary body damage (thiamine) | Hippocampus = new memory encoding = anterograde amnesia when damaged."},
/*35*/ {"q":"In Perforation of Posterior wall of Duodenum, which artery is involved?","o":["Left gastric artery","Gastroduodenal artery","Superior mesenteric artery","Splenic artery"],"a":1,"e":"Posterior duodenal wall perforation (D1) erodes the gastroduodenal artery (GDA) lying directly behind the first part of the duodenum, causing massive haemorrhage — the classic posterior duodenal ulcer complication.<br><br>Take Notes: posterior D1 ulcer → gastroduodenal artery erosion → massive haemorrhage | Anterior ulcer → free peritoneal perforation | GDA → branch of common hepatic artery | Posterior duodenal wall = GDA = the haemorrhage artery."},
/*36*/ {"q":"Main Lymphatic Drainage of Prostate:","o":["Internal Iliac and External Iliac","Common iliac","External iliac","Internal iliac"],"a":0,"e":"The prostate drains primarily to the internal iliac lymph nodes and also to the external iliac and obturator nodes. The pelvic lymph node dissection for prostate cancer includes internal iliac, obturator, and external iliac nodes.<br><br>Take Notes: prostate lymphatics → internal iliac + external iliac + obturator nodes | Testes → para-aortic nodes (L1-L2) | Scrotum → superficial inguinal | Internal + external iliac = prostate = the pelvic nodal drainage."},
/*37*/ {"q":"Lymphatic drainage of tumour at anal verge:","o":["Superficial inguinal LNs","Deep inguinal LNs","Lumbar LN nodes","Para aortic LN"],"a":0,"e":"The anal verge (below the dentate line) drains to the superficial inguinal lymph nodes. Above the dentate line drains to internal iliac and para-rectal nodes.<br><br>Take Notes: below dentate line → superficial inguinal nodes | Above dentate → internal iliac + para-rectal | Dentate line = lymphatic watershed | Anal verge = below dentate = superficial inguinal."},
/*38*/ {"q":"In RTA Pelvis fracture due to anterior inferior iliac spine avulsion, involvement of which muscle?","o":["Puborectal","Rectofemoral","Iliofemoral","Sartorius"],"a":1,"e":"AIIS avulsion fractures occur from sudden hip flexion, avulsing the origin of rectus femoris. ASIS avulsions involve sartorius + tensor fascia lata.<br><br>Take Notes: AIIS avulsion → rectus femoris | ASIS avulsion → sartorius + TFL | Ischial tuberosity → hamstrings | AIIS = rectus femoris = the avulsion muscle."},
/*39*/ {"q":"Decreased Plasma Level of will lead to:","o":["Dehydration","ANP","Vasopressin","Aldosterone 2"],"a":0,"e":"Decreased plasma volume (dehydration) triggers increased ADH (vasopressin) secretion and activation of the RAAS (aldosterone) to conserve water and sodium. ANP decreases with low filling pressure (dehydration).<br><br>Take Notes: dehydration → ↑ADH + ↑aldosterone + ↓ANP | ANP → released by atrial stretch (increases with volume overload) | ANP = natriuretic = opposes aldosterone | Low plasma volume = dehydration = ↓ANP."},
/*40*/ {"q":"Von Gierke Disease Enzyme:","o":["Glucose 6 Phosphatase","Glucose 6 Phosphokinase","Glycogen phosphorylase","None"],"a":0,"e":"Von Gierke disease (GSD type Ia) is caused by glucose-6-phosphatase deficiency — glycogen cannot be converted to free glucose in the liver/kidney, causing severe fasting hypoglycaemia, hepatomegaly, and lactic acidosis.<br><br>Take Notes: Von Gierke → glucose-6-phosphatase deficiency (GSD type I) | Hypoglycaemia + hepatomegaly + lactic acidosis + hyperuricaemia | Pompe → alpha-1,4-glucosidase (GSD type II) | Glucose-6-phosphatase = Von Gierke = the liver glycogen storage disease."},
/*41*/ {"q":"RBCs are produced due to:","o":["None","Lymphocytic release","Glucose 6 Phosphokinase","Erythropoietin"],"a":3,"e":"Erythropoietin (EPO) is the primary stimulus for RBC production — secreted by peritubular fibroblasts of the kidney in response to hypoxia, stimulating bone marrow erythroid precursors.<br><br>Take Notes: EPO → from kidney peritubular cells → stimulates erythropoiesis | Hypoxia → triggers EPO production | CRF → EPO deficiency → normocytic anaemia | EPO = RBC production = kidney-derived hormone."},
/*42*/ {"q":"A patient had RTA 6 months back and from his youth from events. A patient had RTA. He does not know recent events. He remembers Decreased Plasma will lead to dehydration. ANP. Vasopressin. Decreased Plasma. Aldosterone. A patient had RTA. He has Amnesia. Decreased Plasma Level of Vasopressin will lead to:","o":["Aldosterone","Angiotensin 2","Vasopressin (Antidiuretic Hormone)","Dehydration"],"a":3,"e":"Decreased ADH (vasopressin) levels cause diabetes insipidus — the kidney cannot concentrate urine, producing large volumes of dilute urine (polyuria + polydipsia) leading to dehydration.<br><br>Take Notes: ↓ADH → diabetes insipidus → dilute polyuria → dehydration | Central DI → no ADH production | Nephrogenic DI → kidney unresponsive to ADH | ↓Vasopressin = DI = dehydration from dilute polyuria."},
/*43*/ {"q":"A patient had RTA 6 months back and from his youth from events. He does not know recent events but he remembers events. Which one is involved?","o":["Temporal Lobe","Hippocampus","Thalamus","Frontal Lobe"],"a":1,"e":"Anterograde amnesia (inability to form new memories post-injury) with preserved remote memories = hippocampal damage. The hippocampus encodes new declarative memories; retrieval of old memories uses widespread cortical areas.<br><br>Take Notes: anterograde amnesia → hippocampus | New memory formation → hippocampus required | Old memory retrieval → distributed cortex | Hippocampus damage = anterograde amnesia = the classic RTA amnesia."},
/*44*/ {"q":"Antigens donor reach to T cell — Blood brain barrier. Plasma Cells. Blood thymus barrier:","o":["Plasma Cells","Blood Brain barrier","Blood thymus barrier","In Perforation of Duodenum — Which artery is involved"],"a":2,"e":"The blood-thymus barrier protects developing T cells (thymocytes) from self-antigens during their maturation and selection in the thymus. Donor antigens in transplantation must traverse various barriers to reach T cells for rejection initiation.<br><br>Take Notes: blood-thymus barrier → protects developing T cells from premature antigen exposure | Maintained by → thymic epithelial cells + macrophages | Breakdown → autoimmunity risk | Blood-thymus barrier = T cell education protection = the thymic barrier."},
/*45*/ {"q":"In Perforation of Posterior wall of Duodenum. Which artery is involved? Antigens donor T cell. Blood thymus barrier. In Perforation of Duodenum posterior wall. Gastroduodenal artery. Blood thymus barrier. In Perforation of Duodenum. In Perforation of Posterior wall Prevented by Hassle's corpuscle. Blood Brain Barrier:","o":["Blood Brain barrier","Prevented by Hassle's corpuscles","Blood thymus barrier","In Perforation of Duodenum — Which artery is involved"],"a":1,"e":"Hassall's corpuscles (Hassal's corpuscles) are concentrically arranged epithelial cell whorls in the thymic medulla. They regulate T cell development and tolerance by expressing self-antigens (via AIRE gene), facilitating negative selection and Treg development.<br><br>Take Notes: Hassall's corpuscles → thymic medulla → regulate tolerance + Treg development | AIRE gene → expressed in Hassall's corpuscles → central tolerance | Thymic cortex → positive selection | Hassall's corpuscles = thymic medulla = tolerance regulation."},
/*46*/ {"q":"A patient having abdominal pain. Bleed by Splenic artery — Posterior wall of stomach. Perforation of stomach — Bleed by left gastric artery — lesser curvature. Perforation of posterior wall by left gastric artery. Perforation of posterior wall of duodenum by gastroduodenal artery. Bleed by left gastric artery — posterior wall of stomach. A patient having abdominal pain. Perforation of stomach. Bleed by posterior wall. Duodenounnecrosed which artery is involved?","o":["Gastroduodenal artery","Superior pancreaticoduodenal artery","Celiac trunk","Inferior Mesenteric Artery"],"a":0,"e":"Posterior duodenal ulcer perforation erodes the gastroduodenal artery (GDA) lying behind D1, causing massive upper GI bleeding. This is the classic 'posterior duodenal ulcer complication.'<br><br>Take Notes: posterior D1 ulcer → erodes GDA → massive haemorrhage | Anterior ulcer → free peritoneal perforation | GDA = behind D1 | Posterior duodenal = GDA = the surgical emergency."},
/*47*/ {"q":"After mastectomy for breast cancer female developed winging of scapula. Which is damaged:","o":["Radial nerve damage","Long thoracic nerve damage","Superior Mesenteric Artery","Inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery"],"a":1,"e":"Long thoracic nerve injury during axillary lymph node dissection (in breast cancer surgery) causes serratus anterior paralysis → medial scapular winging.<br><br>Take Notes: mastectomy/axillary dissection → long thoracic nerve at risk → scapular winging | Serratus anterior paralysis → inferior angle lifts on arm forward flexion | Long thoracic nerve = C5-C7 = the mastectomy casualty."},
/*48*/ {"q":"A patient presented with anaemia MCV>100L having tingling. Now His total gastrectomy was done in his past. Diagnosed with anaemia. What is the treatment option?","o":["B (BD+Grey's Anatomy)","Thoracodersal nerve damage","Radial nerve damage","Axillary nerve damage"],"a":0,"e":"Total gastrectomy removes parietal cells (intrinsic factor source), causing Vitamin B12 malabsorption → macrocytic megaloblastic anaemia + subacute combined degeneration of cord (tingling/weakness). Treatment: lifelong IM B12 injections (cannot absorb oral B12).<br><br>Take Notes: total gastrectomy → no intrinsic factor → B12 deficiency → megaloblastic anaemia + SACD | Treatment → IM B12 injections (bypass gut absorption) | B12 deficiency SACD → posterior column + lateral column degeneration | Total gastrectomy = B12 IM = the treatment."},
/*49*/ {"q":"Folic acid. Injection Folic acid. True Regarding Primary motor cortex:","o":["Iron","Folic acid","Injection Vitamin B12","True Regarding Primary motor"],"a":1,"e":"Folic acid (Vitamin B9) deficiency causes megaloblastic anaemia with raised MCV but WITHOUT the neurological features of B12 deficiency (no subacute combined degeneration). Neural tube defects occur with periconceptional folate deficiency.<br><br>Take Notes: folate deficiency → megaloblastic anaemia (no neurological features) | B12 deficiency → megaloblastic + SACD (neurological) | Key distinction → neurology present = B12 deficient | Folate = macrocytic anaemia without neurology = the key difference from B12."},
/*50*/ {"q":"True Regarding Primary motor cortex:","o":["Receives sensory input and gives motor response accordingly","Is present only in frontal lobe","Does not receive sensory input","Is involved in coordination of the smoother movements"],"a":0,"e":"The primary motor cortex (M1, Brodmann area 4, precentral gyrus) receives sensory feedback from the somatosensory cortex to refine motor commands — it is not purely motor. It gives rise to the corticospinal tract and receives input from S1, premotor, and supplementary motor areas.<br><br>Take Notes: primary motor cortex → precentral gyrus (Brodmann 4) | Receives sensory input from S1 + premotor | Gives motor output via corticospinal tract | M1 = receives sensory + gives motor = the motor output centre."}
,
/*51*/ {"q":"In Statistical analysis synonym for Universe is:","o":["Sample","Element","Frequency","Population"],"a":3,"e":"In statistics, the 'universe' or 'population' refers to the entire group of individuals or items that a study aims to describe or draw inferences about. A sample is a subset drawn from the population.<br><br>Take Notes: population = universe (entire group of interest) | Sample = subset of the population | Sampling frame = the list from which sample is drawn | Population = universe = the statistical synonym."},
/*52*/ {"q":"After a road traffic accident massive blood loss patient undergoes shock MAP < 60mmhg. Will activate now:","o":["Scurvy","Marasmus","Rickets","CNS Ischemic response"],"a":3,"e":"At MAP <60 mmHg, baroreceptors are overwhelmed and the CNS ischaemic response activates — maximal sympathetic discharge from the vasomotor centre causing intense vasoconstriction to maintain cerebral and coronary perfusion.<br><br>Take Notes: MAP <60 → CNS ischaemic response (last-resort BP mechanism) | Baroreceptors → effective only 60-180 mmHg | CNS ischaemic response = Cushing's reflex equivalent | MAP <60 = CNS ischaemia = maximal sympathetic discharge."},
/*53*/ {"q":"PP = Systolic – Diastolic = 83-60=23. MAP = Diastolic + 1/3rd PP = 60 + 47/6.5 = 67.6. Laparotomy done by an intern. To wash the pelvic brim and goes to wound:","o":["Subphrenic","Right and Left Parasacral","Pelvic brim","Right & Left Perivascular"],"a":1,"e":"During laparotomy, fluid used to wash the pelvic cavity pools in the paracolic gutters and pelvic recesses. The right and left parasacral spaces (pararectal fossae) are the most dependent positions in the pelvis for fluid collection in the supine patient.<br><br>Take Notes: pelvic fluid in supine → pararectal/parasacral fossae (most dependent) | Standing/erect → pouch of Douglas (rectouterine) in females | Right paracolic gutter → most dependent supramesocolic position | Parasacral = pelvic fluid = dependent position."},
/*54*/ {"q":"When thoracocentesis is done in mid axillary lines. 9th intercostal nerve damage:","o":["Right and Left Perivascular","Subphrenic","Right & Left Parasacral","Right & Left Perivascular"],"a":1,"e":"Thoracocentesis in the mid-axillary line at the 9th intercostal space enters the pleural cavity. Damage to the 9th intercostal nerve causes intercostal neuralgia with dermatome-specific pain along the 9th rib territory (upper abdomen/lower thorax).<br><br>Take Notes: thoracocentesis site → above upper border of rib below (to avoid intercostal NVB) | 9th ICS mid-axillary → safe pleural entry | Intercostal NVB → lower border of rib (VAN = vein, artery, nerve) | 9th intercostal nerve = thoracocentesis casualty = lower rib border."},
/*55*/ {"q":"Cause of Fat necrosis in breast:","o":["Fat Embolism","Trauma","Peritonitis","Pancreatitis"],"a":1,"e":"Fat necrosis of the breast is most commonly caused by trauma (seat belt injury, surgical trauma, biopsy). It mimics carcinoma clinically and radiologically (calcified irregular mass) but is benign. Pancreatitis causes fat necrosis of peripancreatic adipose tissue.<br><br>Take Notes: breast fat necrosis → trauma (most common) | Mimics carcinoma (irregular calcified mass on imaging) | Oil cyst → benign sequela | Trauma = breast fat necrosis = benign mimic of carcinoma."},
/*56*/ {"q":"A patient with pyloric stenosis. High serum bicarb:","o":["Decrease PT","Decrease FDP","Increase PT","High serum bicarb"],"a":3,"e":"Pyloric stenosis causes repeated vomiting of HCl, producing hypochloraemic metabolic alkalosis with elevated serum bicarbonate (HCO3- retained to compensate for Cl- loss). Hypokalaemia coexists from renal K+ wasting.<br><br>Take Notes: pyloric stenosis → loss HCl → hypochloraemic + ↑HCO3- + metabolic alkalosis + hypokalaemia | Paradoxical aciduria → late (kidneys excrete H+ to conserve K+) | High serum bicarb = the metabolic marker | Elevated HCO3- = pyloric stenosis = metabolic alkalosis."},
/*57*/ {"q":"Pregnant female with labour pain was admitted in emergency for C section and suddenly dies. Prepared for C section. Dies due to:","o":["Decreased Ph","Hypovolemia","Fat embolism","Amniotic fluid embolism"],"a":3,"e":"Sudden maternal collapse during or after delivery with DIC and cardiorespiratory failure = amniotic fluid embolism (AFE). Amniotic fluid enters maternal circulation causing anaphylactoid reaction, pulmonary hypertension, and DIC.<br><br>Take Notes: sudden peripartum collapse + DIC → amniotic fluid embolism | High mortality (up to 80%) | Triggers → uterine contractions + placental tears | AFE = DIC + collapse = the acute peripartum catastrophe."},
/*58*/ {"q":"First manifestation of vitamin A deficiency:","o":["Amniotic fluid embolism","Pulmonary thromboembolism","Air embolism","Night blindness"],"a":3,"e":"Night blindness (nyctalopia) is the earliest clinical manifestation of Vitamin A deficiency — rod photoreceptors depend on retinol (Vitamin A) for rhodopsin synthesis. Later stages include Bitot's spots, xerophthalmia, and keratomalacia.<br><br>Take Notes: Vitamin A deficiency → night blindness (earliest) → Bitot's spots → xerophthalmia → keratomalacia | Rhodopsin = retinol-opsin | Bitot's spots = white foamy conjunctival deposits | Night blindness = Vitamin A = the first sign."},
/*59*/ {"q":"First 2 cm of duodenum which artery supply?","o":["Vasicularization","Night blindness","Bitot spot","Gastroduodenal artery"],"a":3,"e":"The first 2 cm of the duodenum (cap/bulb) is supplied by the supraduodenal artery (branch of gastroduodenal artery). Posterior D1 is directly related to the GDA, making posterior ulcers prone to GDA erosion.<br><br>Take Notes: first 2 cm duodenum → supraduodenal branch of GDA | Posterior D1 → GDA directly behind (haemorrhage risk) | Distal duodenum → inferior pancreaticoduodenal (SMA) | First 2 cm = GDA branch = supraduodenal artery."},
/*60*/ {"q":"Right gastric artery is branch of:","o":["A>B (BD)","Superior pancreaticoduodenal Artery","Celiac Artery","Inferior pancreaticoduodenal Artery"],"a":0,"e":"The right gastric artery arises from the hepatic artery proper and runs along the lesser curvature of the stomach from right to left, anastomosing with the left gastric artery (from coeliac trunk).<br><br>Take Notes: right gastric artery → hepatic artery proper (coeliac → common hepatic → hepatic proper) | Left gastric artery → directly from coeliac trunk | Both supply lesser curvature | Right gastric = hepatic proper = lesser curvature supply."},
/*61*/ {"q":"Which hormone responsible for delayed gastric emptying?","o":["CCK","Somatostatin","Glucagon","Gastrin"],"a":0,"e":"CCK (from duodenal I cells) delays gastric emptying while stimulating gallbladder contraction and pancreatic enzyme secretion — coordinating digestion of fat and protein entering the duodenum.<br><br>Take Notes: CCK → delays gastric emptying + GB contraction + pancreatic enzymes | Gastrin → promotes gastric emptying (speeds) | Secretin → inhibits gastric emptying + pancreatic HCO3- | CCK = delayed gastric emptying = fat/protein signal."},
/*62*/ {"q":"Excessive movement of his arm. Doctor Diagnosed him. Subclavian steal syndrome. Which of the following is probably stolen in this syndrome?","o":["Vertebral artery","Thyrocervical trunk","Internal carotid","Cerebral artery"],"a":0,"e":"Subclavian steal syndrome occurs when proximal subclavian artery stenosis causes retrograde flow in the vertebral artery — blood is 'stolen' from the vertebrobasilar circulation to supply the arm during exercise, causing posterior circulation ischaemia.<br><br>Take Notes: subclavian steal → vertebral artery reverses flow (retrograde) | Symptoms → vertebrobasilar ischaemia on arm exercise | Proximal subclavian stenosis → the cause | Vertebral artery = the stolen vessel = subclavian steal."},
/*63*/ {"q":"Sexually active female. Presents with Dysuria. A gram positive organism is seen on microscopy. Which organism is causative agent?","o":["Neisseria","Lactobacillus","Gonorrhoea","Pseudomonas"],"a":1,"e":"Normal vaginal flora is dominated by Lactobacillus species (gram-positive rods) which maintain the acidic vaginal environment. In a sexually active woman with dysuria and gram-positive organisms on microscopy (without evidence of pathogen), Lactobacillus is most likely the commensal organism seen.<br><br>Take Notes: vaginal gram-positive organisms → Lactobacillus (normal flora, gram-positive rods) | Maintains vaginal pH <4.5 | Neisseria (gonorrhoea) → gram-negative intracellular diplococci | Lactobacillus = normal vaginal flora = gram-positive rods."},
/*64*/ {"q":"Percentage of Fat needed in diet:","o":["10 to 15%","25% to 30%","30%/60-40%","50-60%"],"a":1,"e":"Dietary fat should constitute 25-30% of total energy intake (WHO/FAO guidelines). Saturated fat should be <10%, with the remainder as unsaturated fats. Too little fat impairs fat-soluble vitamin absorption.<br><br>Take Notes: dietary fat → 25-30% of total energy (WHO guidelines) | Saturated fat → <10% | Carbohydrates → 55-60% | Protein → 10-15% | 25-30% = fat = the recommended dietary proportion."},
/*65*/ {"q":"A patient presented with excessive parasympathetic system causing sweat glands stimulation. What?","o":["Parasympathetic system causes sweat glands","Increase secretions","Decrease secretions","Increase Ductal Contractions"],"a":1,"e":"Parasympathetic (cholinergic muscarinic) stimulation of sweat glands increases secretions. Although sweat glands are sympathetically innervated, they use acetylcholine (muscarinic) as their neurotransmitter — making them responsive to parasympathomimetic drugs.<br><br>Take Notes: sweat glands → sympathetically innervated BUT cholinergic (ACh) | Muscarinic receptor stimulation → increased sweat secretion | Anticholinergics → reduce sweating | Sweating = sympathetic + cholinergic = the unique exception."},
/*66*/ {"q":"Patient came with generalised edema. Urine complete examination reveal Proteinuria. Cause of disease is:","o":["Low Oncotic Pressure","Increased Oncotic Pressure","Portal HTN","Increased Hydrostatic Pressure"],"a":0,"e":"Generalised oedema + proteinuria = nephrotic syndrome. Massive proteinuria → hypoalbuminaemia → reduced plasma oncotic pressure → oedema. This is the primary mechanism of generalised oedema in renal disease.<br><br>Take Notes: nephrotic oedema → proteinuria → ↓albumin → ↓oncotic pressure → oedema | Nephritic → haematuria + oliguria + HTN (inflammatory) | Massive proteinuria (>3.5g/day) = nephrotic | Low oncotic pressure = nephrotic oedema = the mechanism."},
/*67*/ {"q":"BCG features of hypokalemia:","o":["U waves","Peaked T waves","Flattened T waves","Wide QRS"],"a":0,"e":"ECG features of hypokalaemia: prominent U waves (after T wave), flattened/inverted T waves, ST depression, and prolonged QU interval. Peaked T waves are the ECG sign of hyperkalaemia (opposite).<br><br>Take Notes: hypokalaemia ECG → prominent U waves + flattened T waves + ST depression | Hyperkalaemia → peaked T waves + wide QRS + sine wave pattern | U waves = hypokalaemia = the classic ECG sign."},
/*68*/ {"q":"Common virus after blood transfusions:","o":["Hepatitis A","Hepatitis C","Hepatitis B","Hepatitis D"],"a":1,"e":"HCV is the most common viral infection transmitted by blood transfusion in regions with HBV screening programs. Before anti-HCV screening (pre-1990), HCV caused most post-transfusion hepatitis cases.<br><br>Take Notes: post-transfusion hepatitis → HCV (most common in screened blood) | HBV → also blood-borne but well-screened | HAV/HEV → faecal-oral only | HCV = transfusion hepatitis = the post-screening era risk."},
/*69*/ {"q":"Which of the following is a Pain Mediator?","o":["Bradykinin","Histamine","Serotonin","Prostaglandin"],"a":0,"e":"Bradykinin is the most potent pain mediator — it directly stimulates nociceptors (free nerve endings) and also causes vasodilation and increased vascular permeability. It is released from kininogen by the enzyme kallikrein during tissue injury.<br><br>Take Notes: bradykinin → most potent pain mediator | Also → vasodilation + ↑vascular permeability | Prostaglandins → sensitise nociceptors (don't directly cause pain) | Bradykinin = the primary pain-producing mediator."},
/*70*/ {"q":"Portal vein is present in free edge:","o":["Greater sac","Eploric foramen","Lesser sac","Lesser omentum"],"a":3,"e":"The portal vein (with the hepatic artery and common bile duct) runs in the free edge of the lesser omentum (hepatoduodenal ligament). This free edge forms the anterior boundary of the epiploic foramen (foramen of Winslow).<br><br>Take Notes: hepatoduodenal ligament (free edge of lesser omentum) → portal vein + hepatic artery + CBD | Epiploic foramen → posterior to free edge | Pringle manoeuvre → compresses free edge → controls hepatic blood flow | Portal vein = free edge of lesser omentum = the hepatoduodenal ligament."},
/*71*/ {"q":"A 7-year-old child is apathetic and lethargic. On examination coarse hairs. Hepatosplenomegaly and edema. Investigations show low albumin and low ca and vit D levels. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Celiac Disease","Kwashiorkor","Ricketts","Marasmus"],"a":1,"e":"Coarse hair, hepatomegaly, oedema (hypoalbuminaemia), apathy, and low albumin in a child = kwashiorkor (protein deficiency). Low Vitamin D is a secondary complication of malabsorption in this state.<br><br>Take Notes: kwashiorkor → protein deficiency → hypoalbuminaemia + oedema + fatty liver + apathy + flaky skin | Marasmus → calorie deficiency → wasted (no oedema) | Coarse hair + oedema + low albumin = kwashiorkor | Protein deficiency = kwashiorkor = the oedematous malnutrition."},
/*72*/ {"q":"A 17-year-old boy presented nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. Surgeon decided to ligate the culprit blood vessel, epistaxis and clamp. Which vessel is this?","o":["Internal maxillary artery","External maxillary artery","Internal jugular vein","Palatine artery"],"a":0,"e":"Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is supplied primarily by the internal maxillary artery (branch of ECA). Preoperative embolisation of the internal maxillary artery reduces intraoperative haemorrhage. The sphenopalatine artery (branch of internal maxillary) is the direct feeder.<br><br>Take Notes: juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma → internal maxillary artery (ECA branch) | Sphenopalatine artery → direct feeder branch | Preoperative embolisation → reduces haemorrhage | Internal maxillary artery = angiofibroma = the feeding vessel."},
/*73*/ {"q":"Sublingual nitroglycerin given it will be absorbed through Which vein?","o":["Lingual","Sublingual","Dorsal lingual","Submental"],"a":1,"e":"Sublingual nitroglycerine is absorbed through the sublingual veins, which drain directly into the systemic circulation (facial vein → internal jugular vein → SVC) — bypassing first-pass hepatic metabolism.<br><br>Take Notes: sublingual absorption → sublingual veins → facial vein → internal jugular → systemic | Avoids first-pass metabolism | Onset → 1-3 minutes (rapid) | Sublingual veins = nitroglycerine absorption = bypasses liver."},
/*74*/ {"q":"Lymph nodes of lower lip are:","o":["Deep cervical","Sub mental","Parotid","Sublingual"],"a":1,"e":"The midline lower lip drains to the submental lymph nodes. Lateral lower lip drains to submandibular nodes. Both eventually drain to deep cervical nodes.<br><br>Take Notes: midline lower lip → submental nodes | Lateral lower lip → submandibular | Upper lip → submandibular + parotid | Submental = lower lip = the primary draining node."},
/*75*/ {"q":"TB ulcer feature is:","o":["Everted","Punched Out","Sloping","Undermined"],"a":3,"e":"Tuberculous ulcers have undermined edges — the ulcer undermines the surrounding tissue giving the characteristic overhanging edge appearance. This distinguishes TB ulcers from malignant (everted, rolled) and arterial (punched out) ulcers.<br><br>Take Notes: TB ulcer → undermined edges | Carcinoma → everted/rolled edges | Arterial ulcer → punched out (well-defined) | Venous ulcer → sloping edges | Undermined = TB = the classic ulcer edge."},
/*76*/ {"q":"An old woman with short height, Peri-Oral Anaesthesia, Tingling Sensations, having blood Ca Level 6 (normal 8-9), Low Phosphate, High PTH, High ALP and Normal Creatinine. What will be the cause?","o":["Vitamin D deficiency","Primary hypoparathyroidism","Secondary Hyperparathyroidism","Primary Hyperparathyroidism"],"a":0,"e":"Low Ca, low phosphate, high PTH (compensatory), high ALP (bone turnover), normal creatinine = Vitamin D deficiency (osteomalacia). The low Ca triggers secondary hyperparathyroidism (high PTH), and ALP rises from increased bone turnover.<br><br>Take Notes: low Ca + low phosphate + high PTH + high ALP + normal creatinine → Vitamin D deficiency (osteomalacia) | Primary hyperparathyroidism → high Ca + low phosphate | Secondary hyperparathyroidism → low Ca + high PTH (response to CRF or Vit D deficiency) | Vitamin D deficiency = osteomalacia = high PTH + low Ca."},
/*77*/ {"q":"After Gastrectomy a patient presented with Macrocytic anaemia. Most likely cause:","o":["Iron deficiency anemia","Fat malabsorption","Pernicious anemia","Blood loss anemia"],"a":2,"e":"Total/partial gastrectomy removes parietal cells → no intrinsic factor → Vitamin B12 malabsorption → megaloblastic (macrocytic) anaemia. This is essentially an acquired pernicious anaemia picture.<br><br>Take Notes: gastrectomy → no parietal cells → no IF → B12 malabsorption → macrocytic anaemia | Treatment → IM B12 injections | Classic pernicious anaemia → autoimmune parietal cell destruction | Post-gastrectomy macrocytic = pernicious-type = B12 deficiency."},
/*78*/ {"q":"A Patient presented with chronic smoking. Small cell carcinoma of lung confirmed on Biopsy. What will be secreted from oat cells?","o":["ACTH","Insulin","Glucagon","Androgen"],"a":0,"e":"Small cell (oat cell) carcinoma is a neuroendocrine tumour that commonly produces ectopic ACTH (causing Cushing's syndrome) and ADH (causing SIADH). ACTH production is the most classic paraneoplastic syndrome of small cell lung cancer.<br><br>Take Notes: small cell lung cancer → ectopic ACTH (Cushing's) + ADH (SIADH) | Squamous cell → PTHrP (hypercalcaemia) | Adenocarcinoma → HPOA | ACTH = small cell = ectopic Cushing's."},
/*79*/ {"q":"A patient presented with history of RTA. He had fractures and died after 2 days in hospital. Cause of death most likely is:","o":["Fat embolism","Hypotension","Amniotic fluid embolism","Hypertension"],"a":0,"e":"Death 24-72 hours after long bone fractures with no other obvious cause = fat embolism syndrome. Fat globules from fractured bone marrow enter circulation causing pulmonary (dyspnoea), cerebral (petechiae, confusion), and cutaneous (petechial rash) involvement.<br><br>Take Notes: death 2-3 days post-fracture → fat embolism syndrome | Cerebral petechiae on autopsy = pathognomonic | Classic triad → respiratory distress + neurological signs + petechial rash | Fat embolism = post-fracture 24-72h = the classic delayed death."},
/*80*/ {"q":"Paracetamol intoxication is reversed by:","o":["N acetyl cysteine","Codeine","Naloxone","Phenobarbitone"],"a":0,"e":"N-acetylcysteine (NAC) is the antidote for paracetamol (acetaminophen) overdose — it replenishes glutathione stores, preventing toxic NAPQI accumulation in hepatocytes. It is most effective within 8-10 hours of ingestion.<br><br>Take Notes: paracetamol overdose → NAPQI accumulation (glutathione depleted) → hepatocellular necrosis | Antidote → N-acetylcysteine (replenishes glutathione) | Naloxone → opioid antagonist (not paracetamol) | NAC = paracetamol antidote = glutathione precursor."},
/*81*/ {"q":"Lymphatic drainage of Medial Quadrant of breast includes which of the following?","o":["Internal mammary","Subcapsular","Pectoral","Diaphragmatic"],"a":0,"e":"The medial quadrant of the breast (medial half) drains primarily to the internal mammary (parasternal) lymph nodes, which run alongside the internal thoracic artery. Lateral/axillary quadrants drain to axillary nodes.<br><br>Take Notes: medial breast quadrant → internal mammary (parasternal) nodes | Lateral quadrant → axillary nodes (main drainage, 75%) | Upper outer quadrant → most common breast cancer location | Internal mammary = medial quadrant = the parasternal chain."},
/*82*/ {"q":"Referred pain from ureteric colic is felt in thigh due to the involvement of which nerve:","o":["Subcostal","Iliohypogastric","Ilioinguinal","Genitofemoral"],"a":3,"e":"Ureteric colic refers pain to the medial thigh via the genitofemoral nerve (genital branch). The ilioinguinal and iliohypogastric nerves carry pain to the groin and lower abdomen; the genitofemoral nerve specifically refers to the scrotum/labia and medial thigh.<br><br>Take Notes: ureteric colic → flank to groin (T11-L1) | Medial thigh referral → genitofemoral nerve (genital branch) | Testicular referral → genitofemoral (femoral branch) | Genitofemoral = medial thigh = ureteric colic referral nerve."},
/*83*/ {"q":"Posteriorly inferior limit of lung which we called posterior inferior lobe is auscultated at level of:","o":["T10","T11","T12","T7"],"a":0,"e":"The posterior inferior margin of the lung is at T10 during quiet respiration. On deep inspiration, the lung descends to T12. The pleura extends 2 vertebral levels below the lung margin (to T12 posteriorly; pleural reflection to L1 at midline).<br><br>Take Notes: posterior lung margin → T10 (quiet breathing) | Descends to T12 (deep inspiration) | Pleural reflection → 2 levels below lung (T12 posteriorly) | T10 = posterior inferior lung margin = auscultation level."},
/*84*/ {"q":"A Female athlete had an injection given on 14th day of her menstrual cycle to delay menstruation. Which injection could be:","o":["Anti progestrogenic affect","Human chorionic gonadotropin","FSH","Progesterone"],"a":3,"e":"Progesterone injection in the mid-cycle delays menstruation by maintaining endometrial progesterone levels, preventing withdrawal bleeding. This is used by athletes to avoid menstruation during competition. Option E (Progesterone) is the correct answer.<br><br>Take Notes: delay menstruation → progesterone injection (day 14) | Progesterone withdrawal = menstruation trigger | Athletes → use progestins to time competition | Day 14 injection = progesterone = menstrual delay."},
/*85*/ {"q":"Left lower lobe lung differ from right upper lobe lung by not having:","o":["Anterior basal","Medial basal","Apical Segment","Lateral basal"],"a":2,"e":"The apical segment (Nelson's segment/superior segment of lower lobe) is present in ALL lower lobes. The right upper lobe has an apical segment (with posterior and anterior), while the left lower lobe lacks the medial basal segment (which is present in the right lower lobe) — it has only 4 basal segments vs right's 4. The left lower lobe lacks the medial basal segment, not the apical.<br><br>Take Notes: left lower lobe → 4 segments (no medial basal, only 4 basal) | Right lower lobe → 5 segments (medial basal present) | Apical segment → present in all lower lobes | Left lower lobe = no medial basal = the absent segment."},
/*86*/ {"q":"Small saphenous vein is accompanied by:","o":["Sural Nerve","Tibial Nerve","Femoral Nerve","Sciatic Nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The small (short) saphenous vein runs posterior to the lateral malleolus up the posterior calf, accompanied by the sural nerve throughout its course before draining into the popliteal vein behind the knee.<br><br>Take Notes: small saphenous vein → posterior lateral malleolus → popliteal vein | Accompanied by → sural nerve (lateral cutaneous of calf) | Great saphenous → anterior medial malleolus → saphenous nerve | Sural nerve = small saphenous companion = the posterior calf nerve."},
/*87*/ {"q":"A female complained of body aches. Having malar rash. Her ANA is also positive. What next investigation to confirm it?","o":["Anti ds DNA","Anti cardiolipin","Anti CCP","Anti Ro"],"a":0,"e":"Malar rash + ANA positive in a young woman = SLE until proven otherwise. The next confirmatory test is anti-double stranded DNA (anti-dsDNA) antibody — it is highly specific for SLE (95% specificity) and correlates with disease activity.<br><br>Take Notes: SLE confirmation → anti-dsDNA (most specific, 95% specificity) | Anti-Smith → also specific but less sensitive | Anti-CCP → rheumatoid arthritis | Anti-dsDNA = SLE = the confirmatory antibody."},
/*88*/ {"q":"The yeast species that are resistant to echinocandins are?","o":["Candida albicans","Candida krusi","Candida auris","Aspergillus"],"a":2,"e":"Candida auris is an emerging multidrug-resistant yeast resistant to echinocandins, azoles, and often amphotericin B. It causes nosocomial outbreaks with high mortality in ICU patients.<br><br>Take Notes: echinocandin resistance → Candida auris (MDR emerging pathogen) | Candida krusei → intrinsically azole-resistant | Candida albicans → echinocandin sensitive | C. auris = MDR = echinocandin resistant yeast."},
/*89*/ {"q":"In trace of JVP the wave produced by Right Ventricular Contraction Is:","o":["C wave","V wave","X descent","Y descent"],"a":0,"e":"The C wave in the JVP is produced by tricuspid valve closure and bulging back into the right atrium at the onset of right ventricular contraction. It follows the A wave and precedes the X descent.<br><br>Take Notes: JVP C wave → tricuspid valve closure + RV contraction | A wave → atrial contraction | V wave → venous filling (passive) | X descent → atrial relaxation | C wave = RV contraction = tricuspid closure bulge."},
/*90*/ {"q":"Patient has cavernous sinus thrombosis first sign will be:","o":["Ptosis","Loss of upward and medial rotation of eye ball","Loss of abduction","Loss of Adduction"],"a":2,"e":"CN VI (abducens) is affected first in cavernous sinus thrombosis because it runs freely inside the sinus (not in the lateral wall). First sign = loss of lateral gaze (abduction) of the eye.<br><br>Take Notes: cavernous sinus thrombosis → CN VI first (loss of abduction) | CN III + IV + V1/V2 → lateral wall (later affected) | CN VI = freely in sinus = most vulnerable | Loss of abduction = CN VI = first cavernous sinus sign."},
/*91*/ {"q":"Regarding pulmonary varix which is true?","o":["Drain into left atrium","Drain into right atrium","It is distal to pulmonary vein","Normal in venous phase"],"a":0,"e":"A pulmonary varix is a tortuous dilatation of a pulmonary vein, which drains into the left atrium. It appears as a round perihilar opacity on CXR that changes with Valsalva manoeuvre (filling and emptying with venous pressure changes).<br><br>Take Notes: pulmonary varix → dilated pulmonary vein → drains into left atrium | Changes with Valsalva → distinguishes from solid mass | Benign condition | Pulmonary varix = left atrium = pulmonary venous system."},
/*92*/ {"q":"Along with thermoreceptors pain receptors will carry sensation for which of the following?","o":["Freezing Cold","Cold","Hot","Warmth"],"a":0,"e":"Thermoreceptors and nociceptors (pain receptors) both respond to extreme temperatures. Specifically, TRPA1 channels respond to freezing cold temperatures AND noxious stimuli — both thermoreception and nociception. The C-fibres carry pain and temperature together.<br><br>Take Notes: thermoreceptors + pain receptors → co-stimulated by extreme temperatures (freezing cold + burning heat) | TRPV1 → heat + capsaicin | TRPA1 → cold + noxious | Freezing cold = both thermoreceptors + pain receptors activated."},
/*93*/ {"q":"Thyroid hormone receptor present in which of following?","o":["Inside nucleus","Cytoplasm","Cell membrane","G protein coupled receptor"],"a":0,"e":"Thyroid hormone (T3/T4) receptors are nuclear receptors — they are located inside the nucleus and act as transcription factors when activated. T3 binds nuclear receptors to regulate gene expression (not cell membrane receptors).<br><br>Take Notes: thyroid hormone receptor → nuclear receptor (inside nucleus) | T3 enters cell freely (lipophilic) → binds nuclear TR | Contrast with peptide hormones → cell surface receptors (GPCR/enzyme-linked) | Nuclear = thyroid hormone = the intranuclear receptor."},
/*94*/ {"q":"Cyclic AMP Pathway is started by which of the following?","o":["Receptors","Enzyme","Carrier Proteins","Outer Cell Membrane"],"a":0,"e":"The cAMP second messenger pathway is initiated by G-protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs) on the cell surface — ligand binding activates Gs protein → activates adenylyl cyclase → converts ATP to cAMP → activates PKA.<br><br>Take Notes: cAMP pathway → GPCR → Gs protein → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP → PKA | Beta-adrenergic receptors → classic cAMP pathway | Gs stimulates; Gi inhibits adenylyl cyclase | Receptors = cAMP pathway initiators = GPCRs."},
/*95*/ {"q":"Structure immediately above subarachnoid space during Lumbar puncture:","o":["Epidural","Arachnoid","Dural","Subarachnoid"],"a":2,"e":"The layers encountered during lumbar puncture from superficial to deep: skin → subcutaneous → supraspinous ligament → interspinous ligament → ligamentum flavum → epidural space → dura mater → subdural → arachnoid → subarachnoid space. Dura mater is immediately above the subarachnoid space.<br><br>Take Notes: immediately above subarachnoid space → dura mater | LP layers → ligamentum flavum → epidural → dura → subdural → arachnoid → subarachnoid (CSF) | Subdural space → between dura and arachnoid | Dura = immediately above subarachnoid = the LP landmark."},
/*96*/ {"q":"During pregnancy the lumen of uterine cavity is obliterated by fusion of which of following?","o":["Myometrium & Endometrium","Decidua basalis & decidua capsularis","Decidua capsularis & decidua parietalis","Decidua Parietalis & decidua basalis"],"a":2,"e":"As the conceptus grows, the decidua capsularis (covering the conceptus on the endometrial side) and the decidua parietalis (lining the rest of the uterus) fuse by about 4 months, obliterating the uterine lumen.<br><br>Take Notes: uterine lumen obliteration → decidua capsularis + decidua parietalis fuse (~4 months) | Decidua basalis → forms maternal part of placenta | Decidua capsularis → covers embryo | Capsularis + parietalis = uterine lumen obliteration."},
/*97*/ {"q":"A muscle that is attached to more than one joint and prevents the excessive movement of proximal joint is called?","o":["Prime mover","Fixator","Agonist","Antagonist"],"a":1,"e":"A fixator is a muscle that stabilises a proximal joint while a more distal joint moves. Muscles crossing multiple joints act as fixators to prevent unintended proximal joint movement during distal motion.<br><br>Take Notes: fixator → stabilises proximal joint during distal movement | Multi-joint muscles → act as fixators at proximal joint | Example → proximal wrist fixators during finger flexion | Fixator = multi-joint stabiliser = prevents excessive proximal movement."},
/*98*/ {"q":"Superfascial sheath of Anterior Surface of Thyroid is derived from:","o":["Prevertebral fascia","Pretracheal fascia","Subcutaneous fat","Muscles"],"a":1,"e":"The thyroid gland is enclosed by the pretracheal layer of the deep cervical fascia (visceral fascia), which provides the fibrous sheath. The superfascial sheath on the anterior surface derives from pretracheal fascia.<br><br>Take Notes: thyroid sheath → pretracheal fascia (visceral layer of deep cervical fascia) | Prevertebral fascia → covers prevertebral muscles (posterior) | Investing layer → most superficial deep cervical fascia | Pretracheal fascia = thyroid capsule = anterior surface sheath."},
/*99*/ {"q":"Pituitary tumor causes most common increase in which of following?","o":["Cortisol","Prolactin","GH","Thyroid harmones"],"a":1,"e":"Prolactinoma is the most common pituitary adenoma (~40% of all pituitary tumours), causing hyperprolactinaemia with galactorrhoea, amenorrhoea, and infertility (women) or hypogonadism (men).<br><br>Take Notes: most common pituitary adenoma → prolactinoma (40%) | Causes → galactorrhoea + amenorrhoea (women) + hypogonadism (men) | Treatment → cabergoline (D2 agonist) | Prolactin = most common pituitary tumour secretion."},
/*100*/ {"q":"Changes in Blood of 50 year old post-menopausal Women:","o":["Increased FSH, LH","Increased GnRH","Decreased FSH, LH","Normal levels of FSH, LH"],"a":0,"e":"After menopause, oestrogen production falls dramatically — this removes the negative feedback on the hypothalamus and pituitary. FSH and LH rise markedly (FSH >25 IU/L, LH elevated) as the pituitary tries to stimulate the failing ovaries.<br><br>Take Notes: menopause → ↓oestrogen → loss of negative feedback → ↑FSH + ↑LH | FSH rises more than LH in menopause | FSH >25 IU/L = menopausal marker | ↑FSH + ↑LH = post-menopause = the hormonal change."}
,
/*101*/ {"q":"In hemostasis the word Gain is for:","o":["Negative feedback","Exaggeration of the Positive feedback","Exaggeration of the negative feedback","Positive feedback"],"a":3,"e":"In haemostasis, 'gain' refers to positive feedback amplification of the clotting cascade — once initiated, thrombin activates factors V, VIII, and XI, rapidly amplifying its own production and accelerating clot formation.<br><br>Take Notes: haemostasis gain → positive feedback (clotting cascade amplification) | Thrombin → activates factors V, VIII, XI (self-amplifying) | Fibrinolysis → negative feedback (limits clot extension) | Gain = positive feedback = clotting cascade amplification."},
/*102*/ {"q":"Level of hyoid bone in erect position?","o":["T1","C5","C3","C4"],"a":2,"e":"The hyoid bone lies at the C3 vertebral level in the erect posture — between the mandible and thyroid cartilage (C4-C5).<br><br>Take Notes: hyoid bone → C3 level | Thyroid cartilage → C4-C5 | Cricoid cartilage → C6 | Hyoid = C3 = the floating neck bone level."},
/*103*/ {"q":"The most common coagulopathy in trauma patients is:","o":["Clotting factor inhibition and depletion","Disseminated intravascular coagulation","Citrate toxicity","Hypofibrinogenaemia"],"a":1,"e":"Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) is the most common coagulopathy in trauma patients — massive tissue injury releases tissue factor, triggering widespread thrombin generation, factor consumption, and secondary fibrinolysis.<br><br>Take Notes: trauma coagulopathy → DIC (most common) | Mechanism → tissue factor release → thrombin → factor consumption | Lab → ↑PT + ↑APTT + ↓platelets + ↑D-dimer | DIC = trauma = the most common coagulopathy."},
/*104*/ {"q":"MI occur due to thrombosis which factor is important and independent of other factors?","o":["Period of Less activity","Endothelial injury","Stasis","Hypercoagubility"],"a":1,"e":"Endothelial injury is the primary trigger for arterial thrombosis (MI) — disruption of the intact endothelium exposes collagen and tissue factor, initiating platelet adhesion and the coagulation cascade. It is independent of stasis or hypercoagulability.<br><br>Take Notes: arterial thrombosis (MI) → endothelial injury (primary factor) | Venous thrombosis (DVT) → Virchow's triad (stasis + hypercoagulability + endothelial injury) | Endothelial injury = the independent MI thrombosis factor | Plaque rupture = endothelial injury = MI trigger."},
/*105*/ {"q":"Muscles of back are supplied by:","o":["Dorsal rami","Dorsal rami of Spinal nerve","Intercostal nerve","Long thoracic nerve"],"a":1,"e":"The intrinsic back muscles (erector spinae, multifidus, etc.) are supplied by the dorsal (posterior) primary rami of the spinal nerves. Each spinal nerve divides into a ventral and dorsal ramus after emerging from the intervertebral foramen.<br><br>Take Notes: intrinsic back muscles → dorsal rami of spinal nerves | Trapezius → accessory nerve (CN XI) | Serratus anterior → long thoracic nerve | Dorsal rami = intrinsic back muscles = the posterior primary ramus supply."},
/*106*/ {"q":"A 26 year male presented to you in surgical ER after penetrating injury to right lateral chest. On examination when he inspire the mediastinum moves to left side and during expiration the shift towards left side is enhanced. What will be the most likely diagnose?","o":["Open pneumothorax","Haemothorax","Tension pneumothorax","Pleurisy"],"a":2,"e":"Mediastinal shift to the OPPOSITE side of the pathology during inspiration (and enhancement during expiration) = tension pneumothorax. Air enters pleural space, cannot escape, builds pressure, pushing mediastinum to the contralateral side.<br><br>Take Notes: mediastinal shift away from lesion → tension pneumothorax | Simple pneumothorax → slight shift on inspiration only | Haemothorax → dullness to percussion (not air) | Tension pneumothorax = mediastinal shift = contralateral displacement."},
/*107*/ {"q":"Blow out fracture of orbit with Proptosis and loss of cheek sensation it is due to:","o":["Cheek edema","Zygoma","Infraorbital nerve damage","Infraorbital nerve entrapment at its formen"],"a":2,"e":"Orbital blowout fracture (floor fracture) causes infraorbital nerve damage producing cheek, upper lip, and upper gum numbness. Diplopia occurs from inferior rectus entrapment. Enophthalmos (not proptosis) is typical — if proptosis occurs, it is from haemorrhage.<br><br>Take Notes: orbital blowout fracture → infraorbital nerve damage → cheek anaesthesia | Inferior rectus entrapment → vertical diplopia | Enophthalmos → sunken eye (fat herniation) | Infraorbital nerve = cheek numbness = blowout fracture sign."},
/*108*/ {"q":"Gastrocnemius size is reduced after cast applied for few weeks of fracture. Most likely due to:","o":["Decrease Blood supply","Decrease muscle caliber","Denervation atrophy","Decrease protein synthesis and increase degradation"],"a":3,"e":"Immobilisation (disuse) atrophy results from decreased mechanical load → reduced mTOR signalling → decreased protein synthesis + increased ubiquitin-proteasome protein degradation → muscle fibre size reduction.<br><br>Take Notes: disuse/cast atrophy → ↓protein synthesis + ↑protein degradation | Denervation → faster + more severe atrophy | Satellite cells → muscle regeneration (preserved in disuse) | ↓Synthesis + ↑degradation = disuse atrophy = the mechanism."},
/*109*/ {"q":"GFR measured clinically by:","o":["K clearance","Creatinine Clearance","Inulin Clearance","Urea"],"a":1,"e":"GFR is clinically estimated by creatinine clearance (Cockcroft-Gault formula) or eGFR (CKD-EPI). Inulin clearance is the gold standard for measuring true GFR (research setting) — inulin is freely filtered and neither secreted nor reabsorbed.<br><br>Take Notes: clinical GFR → creatinine clearance (eGFR) | Gold standard GFR → inulin clearance (research) | Creatinine → slight tubular secretion (overestimates GFR slightly) | Creatinine clearance = clinical GFR = the bedside measurement."},
/*110*/ {"q":"Which of the following structure does aorta compress at Aortic hiatus?","o":["Thoracic duct & Vagus Nerve","Aorta & Vagus Nerve","Aorta & Both Phrenic Nerves","Azygous & Thoracic duct"],"a":3,"e":"The aortic hiatus (T12) transmits the aorta, thoracic duct, and azygous vein. These three structures pass through the aortic opening of the diaphragm together.<br><br>Take Notes: aortic hiatus (T12) → aorta + thoracic duct + azygous vein | Oesophageal hiatus (T10) → oesophagus + vagus nerves | Caval opening (T8) → IVC | Azygous + thoracic duct = compressed with aorta at T12."},
/*111*/ {"q":"A person is having athlete's foot. He presents with red, hot and tender foot with red lines extending up. Organism involved is:","o":["Streptococcus Pyogenes","Tinea Pedis","Staph Aureus","Staph Epidermidis"],"a":0,"e":"Red, hot, tender foot with red lines (lymphangitis — tracking up the lymphatics) indicates acute bacterial cellulitis/lymphangitis, most commonly caused by Group A Streptococcus (S. pyogenes). The red streaks follow lymphatic channels and indicate spreading infection.<br><br>Take Notes: cellulitis + lymphangitis (red streaks) → Group A Streptococcus (most common) | Tinea pedis → fungal (itching + scaling, not lymphangitis) | Staph aureus → also cellulitis but less lymphangitis | Red lines = lymphangitis = Streptococcus pyogenes."},
/*112*/ {"q":"Deep plantar artery is branch of:","o":["Popliteal","Peroneal","Posterior Tibial Artery","Anterior Tibial Artery"],"a":2,"e":"The deep plantar artery is a branch of the dorsalis pedis artery (continuation of anterior tibial artery) that dips between the 1st and 2nd metatarsals to enter the plantar space and form the deep plantar arch. The plantar arch is completed by the lateral plantar artery (from posterior tibial).<br><br>Take Notes: deep plantar artery → from dorsalis pedis (anterior tibial) → between 1st and 2nd metatarsals | Lateral plantar → from posterior tibial | Deep plantar arch = lateral plantar + deep plantar | Posterior tibial → the main plantar supply = the source."},
/*113*/ {"q":"Loss of general sensation in dura of middle cranial fossa due to lesion of:","o":["Facial Nerve","Glossopharyngeal Nerve","Trigeminal Nerve","Vagus Nerve"],"a":3,"e":"The dura of the middle cranial fossa is supplied by meningeal branches of the mandibular nerve (V3, from the trigeminal nerve) and branches from the maxillary nerve (V2). The trigeminal nerve provides general somatic sensation to most of the cranial dura mater.<br><br>Take Notes: middle cranial fossa dura → sensation via trigeminal (V3 mainly) | Posterior fossa dura → vagus + C2 | Anterior fossa → ophthalmic (V1) | Trigeminal = middle cranial fossa dura = sensory supply."},
/*114*/ {"q":"Patient had extremely high BUN/Cr ratio greater than 20 and Decreased Urine output. Cause will be:","o":["Post renal Azotemia","Pre renal azotemia","Acute Tubular Necrosis","CKD"],"a":1,"e":"BUN/Cr ratio >20 with oliguria = pre-renal azotaemia — the kidneys avidly reabsorb urea (but not creatinine) in response to reduced perfusion, disproportionately raising BUN. Urea-creatinine ratio normalises in intrinsic renal disease (<20).<br><br>Take Notes: BUN/Cr >20 + oliguria → pre-renal azotaemia (reduced perfusion) | ATN → BUN/Cr <20 (creatinine rises proportionately) | Pre-renal → responds to fluids | BUN/Cr >20 = pre-renal = the diagnostic ratio."},
/*115*/ {"q":"Which of following structure is posterior to ovarian fossa?","o":["Ureter","Internal iliac","External iliac artery","External iliac vein"],"a":0,"e":"The ovarian fossa is bounded posteriorly by the ureter and internal iliac vessels. The ureter runs posteriorly to the ovarian fossa and is at risk during oophorectomy. The ovarian artery/vein cross the ureter anteriorly.<br><br>Take Notes: posterior to ovarian fossa → ureter + internal iliac vessels | Ovarian vessels → cross ureter anteriorly (at pelvic brim) | Ureter at risk → during oophorectomy | Ureter = posterior to ovarian fossa = the surgical danger structure."},
/*116*/ {"q":"An obese patient wears a tight collar shirt and feels tightness in collar and faint whenever he turns his head. Which of following is responsible for this?","o":["Increase TPR","Increase venous compliance","Increase CO","Increase myocardial contractility"],"a":1,"e":"Tight collar compression of the carotid sinus triggers a vasovagal response — carotid sinus hypersensitivity causes bradycardia, vasodilation (increased venous compliance), and hypotension → syncope. Treatment: carotid sinus massage test + pacemaker if needed.<br><br>Take Notes: carotid sinus pressure → parasympathetic reflex → ↓HR + ↑venous compliance + ↓BP → syncope | Carotid sinus hypersensitivity → exaggerated response | Venous compliance increase = vasodilation = the syncope mechanism | Increased venous compliance = carotid sinus compression = syncope."},
/*117*/ {"q":"Meissner plexus function is:","o":["Volume maintenance","Motility","Secretory activity","Regulate reflexes"],"a":2,"e":"Meissner's plexus (submucosal plexus) primarily regulates GI secretion and mucosal blood flow. Auerbach's plexus (myenteric) primarily controls GI motility. Both form the enteric nervous system.<br><br>Take Notes: Meissner's (submucosal) plexus → secretion + mucosal blood flow | Auerbach's (myenteric) plexus → motility | Hirschsprung → absent myenteric ganglia | Meissner = secretion = the submucosal plexus function."},
/*118*/ {"q":"To check renal function, What is checked on urine specific gravity?","o":["Concentration","Filtration","Secretion","Absorption"],"a":0,"e":"Urine specific gravity (1.001-1.035) reflects the concentration of solutes in urine — it is a simple bedside measure of renal concentrating ability. Isosthenuria (fixed specific gravity = 1.010) indicates loss of concentrating ability (CRF, tubular damage).<br><br>Take Notes: urine specific gravity → measures urine concentration ability | Normal → 1.001-1.035 (wide range) | Isosthenuria → 1.010 fixed (CRF/tubular disease) | Specific gravity = urine concentration = renal concentrating function."},
/*119*/ {"q":"Sjogren syndrome is associated with Risk of developing:","o":["Lupus erythematosus","Rheumatoid arthritis","Hashimoto thyroiditis","Non Hodgkin Lymphoma"],"a":3,"e":"Sjögren's syndrome carries a 44-fold increased risk of developing Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma (particularly MALT lymphoma of the salivary glands/parotid). Option E (Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma) is the correct answer.<br><br>Take Notes: Sjögren's syndrome → 44x increased NHL risk (MALT lymphoma) | Presents → dry eyes + dry mouth + parotid enlargement | Anti-Ro (SS-A) + Anti-La (SS-B) → specific antibodies | Sjögren's = MALT lymphoma = salivary gland NHL."},
/*120*/ {"q":"A mother had history of eating undercooked meat. Baby develops microcephaly and brain calcifications. There is microphthalmia too. Which organism is responsible?","o":["CMV","Toxoplasmosis","Treponema pallidum","Listeria"],"a":1,"e":"Toxoplasmosis (Toxoplasma gondii) from undercooked meat causes congenital infection with the classic triad: chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus/intracranial calcifications, and psychomotor retardation. Microcephaly and microphthalmia also occur.<br><br>Take Notes: undercooked meat + microcephaly + brain calcifications + microphthalmia → congenital toxoplasmosis | Classic triad → chorioretinitis + calcifications + hydrocephalus | CMV → periventricular calcifications | Toxoplasmosis = undercooked meat = intracranial calcifications."},
/*121*/ {"q":"Melanoma Spreads to Brain through:","o":["Sclera","Optic Nerve","Emissary Vein","Retina"],"a":2,"e":"Uveal melanoma (most common primary intraocular tumour in adults) invades the orbit and spreads to the brain through the emissary veins — small vascular channels that penetrate the sclera and communicate with orbital/intracranial vessels.<br><br>Take Notes: uveal melanoma → orbital extension via emissary veins | Emissary veins = scleral penetrations = vascular orbital connections | Most common primary intraocular tumour in adults | Emissary veins = uveal melanoma = brain spread route."},
/*122*/ {"q":"Gram negative bacteria have in their:","o":["Capsule","Outer membrane of cell wall","Cell wall","Cytoplasm"],"a":1,"e":"Gram-negative bacteria have a unique outer membrane containing LPS (lipopolysaccharide/endotoxin) — this outer membrane is absent in gram-positive bacteria. The outer membrane also contains porins for selective permeability and contributes to antibiotic resistance.<br><br>Take Notes: gram-negative unique structure → outer membrane (LPS + porins) | LPS = endotoxin → TLR-4 → septic shock | Gram-positive → thick peptidoglycan (no outer membrane) | Outer membrane = gram-negative = the LPS-containing layer."},
/*123*/ {"q":"Carbonic anhydrase is present in:","o":["Cytoplasm of neutrophil","Cytoplasm of basophil","Cell membrane of RBC","Cytoplasm of RBC"],"a":3,"e":"Carbonic anhydrase is abundant in the cytoplasm of RBCs, catalysing the reversible reaction CO2 + H2O ↔ HCO3- + H+. This enzyme enables rapid CO2 transport from tissues (as bicarbonate) to the lungs.<br><br>Take Notes: carbonic anhydrase → RBC cytoplasm (CO2 transport) | Also → kidney tubular cells (HCO3- reabsorption) | Acetazolamide → CA inhibitor (diuretic + altitude sickness) | RBC cytoplasm = carbonic anhydrase = CO2 transport enzyme."},
/*124*/ {"q":"Complete termination of single skeletal muscle contraction by:","o":["Calcium back into Sarcolemna","Calcium back into Neuromuscular Junction","Ach degradation by Acetylcholinesterase","Blockage of Neuromuscular Junction"],"a":2,"e":"Termination of the skeletal muscle contraction signal occurs when acetylcholinesterase (AChE) at the neuromuscular junction rapidly degrades acetylcholine (ACh), ending the depolarisation signal. Ca2+ is then pumped back into the SR, causing relaxation.<br><br>Take Notes: muscle contraction termination → AChE degrades ACh at NMJ | Ca2+ pumped back into SR → troponin reassociates with tropomyosin → relaxation | AChE inhibitors (organophosphates, neostigmine) → prolong contraction | AChE = the NMJ off-switch = muscle contraction termination."},
/*125*/ {"q":"Patient had RTA and got splenic rupture for which splenectomy was done. What is seen in this patient?","o":["Thrombocytopenia","Howel Jolly bodies","Erythrocytopenia","Reticulocytopenia"],"a":1,"e":"After splenectomy, Howell-Jolly bodies (nuclear remnants in RBCs) appear in peripheral blood — normally removed by the spleen. Other post-splenectomy findings: thrombocytosis, leukocytosis, target cells, and acanthocytes.<br><br>Take Notes: post-splenectomy → Howell-Jolly bodies (nuclear remnants in RBCs) | Also → thrombocytosis + leukocytosis + target cells | Risk → encapsulated organism infection (pneumococcus, meningococcus, H. influenzae) | Howell-Jolly bodies = post-splenectomy = nuclear RBC remnants."},
/*126*/ {"q":"A patient presented with Expressionless face and Ataxia. Examination reveals rigidity. Damage to:","o":["Caudate & Putamen","Globus Pallidus Externa","Globus Pallidus Interna","Subthalamus"],"a":0,"e":"Expressionless face (hypomimia) + ataxia + rigidity = extrapyramidal features suggesting basal ganglia damage. The caudate and putamen (striatum) are the input nuclei of the basal ganglia — damage produces hypokinetic (Parkinsonian) features including rigidity and hypomimia.<br><br>Take Notes: expressionless face + rigidity → striatum (caudate + putamen) damage | Parkinson's → substantia nigra → dopamine depletion → striatal dysfunction | Huntington's → caudate atrophy → chorea | Caudate + putamen = striatum = Parkinsonian features."},
/*127*/ {"q":"Which of the following muscle passes through greater sciatic foramen?","o":["Obturator internus","Obturator Externus","Piriformis","Gemellus superior"],"a":2,"e":"The piriformis muscle is the key structure in the greater sciatic foramen — it passes through the foramen from the sacrum to the greater trochanter, dividing the foramen into supra- and infra-piriform portions.<br><br>Take Notes: piriformis → passes through greater sciatic foramen | Above piriformis → superior gluteal nerve + vessels | Below piriformis → sciatic nerve + inferior gluteal + pudendal | Piriformis = greater sciatic foramen = the landmark muscle."},
/*128*/ {"q":"All of the following attach to greater trochanter except:","o":["Gluteus maximus","Obturator internus","Gluteus Medius","Gluteus Minimus"],"a":0,"e":"The gluteus maximus inserts into the gluteal tuberosity of the femur and the iliotibial tract — NOT the greater trochanter. Obturator internus, gluteus medius, gluteus minimus, piriformis, and gemellus muscles all insert into the greater trochanter.<br><br>Take Notes: greater trochanter insertions → gluteus medius + minimus + obturator internus + piriformis | Gluteus maximus → gluteal tuberosity + ITB (NOT greater trochanter) | Gluteus maximus is the exception | Greater trochanter = NOT gluteus maximus insertion."},
/*129*/ {"q":"A group of mice was taken and injection of plastic hydrocarbon was given. This will work as initiator in process the initiator work as:","o":["Slow process will take time","Memory produce","It is last step in ccarcinogenesis","Cause Clonal proliferation"],"a":1,"e":"Initiators in carcinogenesis cause permanent, irreversible DNA mutations that are memorised (retained) in the cell — even if cell division doesn't occur immediately. This 'memory' of DNA damage is the defining property of initiators.<br><br>Take Notes: initiator → causes permanent DNA mutation (irreversible + remembered) | Promoter → reversible, causes clonal proliferation (no direct DNA damage) | Progression → further mutations → invasive cancer | Initiator = memory = permanent irreversible DNA damage."},
/*130*/ {"q":"Renal capsule supplied by:","o":["Interlobar artery","Interlobular artery","Segmental artery","Renal artery"],"a":1,"e":"The renal capsule (fibrous capsule) is supplied by interlobular arteries (cortical radiate arteries), which arise from the arcuate arteries and run radially through the cortex toward the capsule, giving off afferent arterioles and capsular branches.<br><br>Take Notes: renal capsule → interlobular (cortical radiate) arteries | Blood supply order → renal artery → segmental → interlobar → arcuate → interlobular (cortical radiate) → afferent arterioles | Interlobular = the capsule supply."},
/*131*/ {"q":"Bilateral damage to hippocampus results in:","o":["Disappearance of recent memories","Loss of working memory","Loss of ability to encode events of recent past in long term memory","Anterograde amnesia"],"a":2,"e":"Bilateral hippocampal damage causes anterograde amnesia — specifically loss of ability to form new declarative memories (encode new events into long-term memory). Remote memories (stored in neocortex) remain intact.<br><br>Take Notes: bilateral hippocampal damage → anterograde amnesia (cannot form new long-term memories) | Remote memories → preserved (cortical storage) | HM (famous case) → bilateral hippocampectomy | Hippocampus = memory encoding = anterograde amnesia."},
/*132*/ {"q":"Sickle cell disease due to:","o":["Point mutation","Mismatch repair failure","Missense mutation","Splice mutation"],"a":0,"e":"Sickle cell disease is caused by a point mutation (single nucleotide substitution) in the beta-globin gene — glutamic acid (GAG) → valine (GTG) at position 6. This is also a missense mutation (amino acid change) — specifically a point mutation causing a missense change.<br><br>Take Notes: sickle cell disease → point mutation in beta-globin gene (Glu→Val at position 6) | GAG → GTG (single nucleotide substitution) | Missense mutation (amino acid changed) | Point mutation = SCD = the simplest type of mutation."},
/*133*/ {"q":"About Cardiac plexus:","o":["Formed infront of trachea","Have preganglionic sympathetic fibers from superior cervical ganglia","Contain both sympathetic and parasympathetic fibers","None"],"a":2,"e":"The cardiac plexus contains both sympathetic (from T1-T5 paravertebral ganglia via cardiac nerves) and parasympathetic (from vagus nerve via cardiac branches) fibres. It lies anterior to the tracheal bifurcation.<br><br>Take Notes: cardiac plexus → sympathetic (T1-T5) + parasympathetic (vagus) | Superficial cardiac plexus → below aortic arch | Deep cardiac plexus → anterior to tracheal bifurcation | Both = cardiac plexus = mixed autonomic."},
/*134*/ {"q":"Congenital diaphragmatic hernia occur due to:","o":["Absent Septum transversum","Incomplete pleuroperitoneal membrane","Defect in Right Muscle","Defect in Left Muscle"],"a":1,"e":"Congenital diaphragmatic hernia (CDH) results from incomplete fusion of the pleuroperitoneal membrane — the left posterolateral defect (Bochdalek hernia) is most common (90%), allowing abdominal organs to herniate into the thorax.<br><br>Take Notes: CDH → incomplete pleuroperitoneal membrane closure | Bochdalek hernia → left posterolateral (most common, 90%) | Morgagni hernia → anterior retrosternal | Incomplete pleuroperitoneal membrane = CDH = left posterior defect."},
/*135*/ {"q":"Posterolateral relation to thyroid:","o":["Parathyroid gland","Caroted sheath","Trachea","Sternohyoid"],"a":1,"e":"The carotid sheath (containing common carotid artery, internal jugular vein, and vagus nerve) lies posterolaterally to the thyroid lobe on each side. This is the major posterolateral structure at risk during thyroid surgery.<br><br>Take Notes: posterolateral to thyroid → carotid sheath (CCA + IJV + vagus) | Anterior → sternothyroid + sternohyoid | Posterior → trachea + parathyroids + RLN | Carotid sheath = posterolateral thyroid = the surgical neighbour."},
/*136*/ {"q":"A patient Para 8 with UV prolapse and cervix at introitus. Ligament damage is:","o":["Uterosacral ligament","Transverse cervical ligament","Broad ligament","Round ligament"],"a":1,"e":"Uterovaginal prolapse (procidentia) results from damage to the cardinal (transverse cervical/Mackenrodt's) ligaments — the primary support keeping the cervix and upper vagina in position. Grand multiparity (Para 8) progressively weakens these ligaments.<br><br>Take Notes: uterine prolapse → cardinal/transverse cervical ligament (Mackenrodt's) damage | Primary support → cardinal + uterosacral ligaments | Uterosacral → secondary (posterior support) | Cardinal ligament = transverse cervical = primary prolapse-causing damage."},
/*137*/ {"q":"Gold standard investigation for Low Lying Placenta:","o":["Pelvic USG","Pelvic MRI","Transvaginal USG","Doppler USG"],"a":2,"e":"Transvaginal ultrasound (TVUS) is the gold standard for diagnosing placenta praevia (low-lying placenta) — it provides accurate measurement of the distance between the placental edge and the internal cervical os, with high sensitivity and specificity.<br><br>Take Notes: placenta praevia gold standard → transvaginal ultrasound (TVUS) | More accurate than transabdominal USG | Distance <20mm from internal os = praevia | TVUS = placenta praevia = the gold standard imaging."},
/*138*/ {"q":"First Step in incised wound healing:","o":["Formation of Granulation tissue","Acute Inflammation","Maturation of Scar","Keloid Formation"],"a":1,"e":"The first step in wound healing after incision is acute inflammation (hours 0-72) — vascular response with vasodilatation, oedema, neutrophil influx, and haemostasis. This is followed by proliferation (granulation tissue formation) and maturation (scar remodelling).<br><br>Take Notes: wound healing phases → acute inflammation → granulation tissue → scar maturation | Acute inflammation → first (0-72 hours) | Granulation tissue → days 3-5 | Keloid → abnormal scar (extends beyond wound margins) | Acute inflammation = first step = wound healing initiation."},
/*139*/ {"q":"Patient had difficulty in standing and waddling gait nerve involves:","o":["Sciatic nerve","Femoral nerve","Obturator nerve","Superior gluteal nerve"],"a":3,"e":"Trendelenburg gait (waddling gait) results from superior gluteal nerve injury causing gluteus medius and minimus weakness. The pelvis drops on the contralateral side when standing on the affected limb.<br><br>Take Notes: waddling/Trendelenburg gait → superior gluteal nerve → gluteus medius + minimus weakness | Inferior gluteal → gluteus maximus (extension + stair climbing) | Standing difficulty + waddling = superior gluteal nerve | Superior gluteal = waddling gait = the Trendelenburg nerve."},
/*140*/ {"q":"Boy with H/O trauma to perineal region, swelling in scrotum. Which of the following is Ruptured?","o":["Urethra above urogenital diaphragm","Urethra below urogenital diaphragm","Penile Urethra","Membranous Urethra"],"a":1,"e":"Perineal trauma causing scrotal swelling indicates bulbar urethral rupture (below the urogenital diaphragm). Urine tracks along Colles' fascia (continuous with Dartos/Scarpa's fascia) into the scrotum and anterior abdominal wall.<br><br>Take Notes: bulbar urethra rupture → below urogenital diaphragm → urine in scrotum (Colles' fascia) | Membranous urethra rupture → urine into deep perineal pouch | Prostatic urethra → above UGD → retropubic space | Scrotal urine = bulbar urethra = below urogenital diaphragm."},
/*141*/ {"q":"Upper fibers of external intercostal interdigitate with?","o":["Rectus abdominis","Serratus anterior","Latissmus dorsi","Sclane anterior"],"a":1,"e":"The digitations of serratus anterior interdigitate with the external intercostal muscles and the external oblique muscle. Serratus anterior arises from the outer surfaces of the upper 8-9 ribs, interdigitating with external intercostals between rib attachments.<br><br>Take Notes: serratus anterior → interdigitates with external intercostals + external oblique | Origin → outer surfaces ribs 1-8 | Action → protracts + rotates scapula | Serratus anterior = external intercostal interdigitation = the costal overlap."},
/*142*/ {"q":"After Cut in Skin Bacteria enter it causes inflammation:","o":["Apoptosis of surrounding cell","Activate IFG","Activate NK cell","Activate Lymphocytes"],"a":3,"e":"Bacterial skin infection triggers the innate immune response — complement activation, mast cell degranulation, and cytokine release activate the adaptive immune response via lymphocytes (T and B cells). The initial acute response involves neutrophils, followed by lymphocyte activation.<br><br>Take Notes: bacterial skin infection → innate response first (neutrophils + complement) → then adaptive (lymphocytes) | Lymphocyte activation → antigen-specific response | NK cells → innate (virus + tumour) | Lymphocytes = adaptive = the bacteria-triggered immune cells."},
/*143*/ {"q":"In Right astereognosis involved brain area is:","o":["Left internal capsule","Right internal capsule","Pons","Posterior occipital Lobe"],"a":0,"e":"Astereognosis (inability to recognise objects by touch with intact basic sensation) is a cortical sensory deficit. Right-sided astereognosis results from left-sided parietal lobe (S2) or left internal capsule lesion — since sensory fibres decussate, left hemisphere processes right-sided sensation.<br><br>Take Notes: right astereognosis → left parietal/somatosensory lesion (or left internal capsule) | Sensory fibres → cross at medulla (dorsal columns) | Right sensory deficit = left hemisphere lesion | Left internal capsule = right astereognosis = crossed sensory pathway."},
/*144*/ {"q":"Thoracic duct drains into:","o":["Junction of internal jugular and left subclavian vein","Junction of internal jugular and right subclavian vein","Right subclavian vein","Right internal jugular vein"],"a":0,"e":"The thoracic duct drains into the junction of the left internal jugular vein and left subclavian vein (left venous angle/left brachiocephalic vein). The right lymphatic duct drains into the right venous angle.<br><br>Take Notes: thoracic duct → left venous angle (left IJV + left subclavian junction) | Right lymphatic duct → right venous angle | Thoracic duct → carries most body lymph (from below diaphragm + left side above) | Left venous angle = thoracic duct = the drainage point."},
/*145*/ {"q":"Oxygen exchange in alveolar membrane occurs through process of:","o":["Active transport","Na/k atpase pump","Simple diffusion","Facilitated diffusion"],"a":2,"e":"Gas exchange (O2 and CO2) across the alveolar-capillary membrane occurs by simple diffusion — driven by partial pressure gradients. No energy or carrier proteins are required. Fick's law governs the rate: proportional to surface area × pressure gradient, inversely proportional to membrane thickness.<br><br>Take Notes: alveolar gas exchange → simple diffusion (Fick's law) | O2 → alveolus (104 mmHg) to blood (40 mmHg) | CO2 → blood (45 mmHg) to alveolus (40 mmHg) | Simple diffusion = passive = the gas exchange mechanism."},
/*146*/ {"q":"The ascent of horse shoe shaped kidney is prevented by:","o":["External iliac artery","Internal iliac artery","Superior mesenteric artery","Inferior mesenteric artery"],"a":3,"e":"The horseshoe kidney's ascent is arrested by the inferior mesenteric artery (IMA) at L3, which catches the isthmus connecting the two lower poles as the kidney tries to ascend from the pelvis.<br><br>Take Notes: horseshoe kidney → arrested by IMA at L3 | Isthmus (connecting lower poles) = the structure caught | Horseshoe kidney → usually below IMA | IMA = L3 = the horseshoe kidney ascent barrier."},
/*147*/ {"q":"Woman with blood group RH-ve and give birth to O-ve baby. Newborn has mismatch haemorrhage disease. Mother should take what to prevent haemolytic disease of newborn in next baby?","o":["Anti D Immunoglobulin","No Reaction in next Pregnancy","No Need to give Anti D Antibodies","Tetanus prophylaxis"],"a":0,"e":"Anti-D immunoglobulin (Rhogam) given within 72 hours of delivery destroys fetal RhD-positive RBCs that may have entered the maternal circulation, preventing sensitisation and future haemolytic disease of the newborn (HDN) in subsequent RhD-positive pregnancies.<br><br>Take Notes: Rh-negative mother + Rh-positive baby → risk of sensitisation → HDN in future pregnancies | Prevention → anti-D immunoglobulin within 72 hours of delivery | Also given → at 28 weeks (routine) + after any sensitising event | Anti-D immunoglobulin = HDN prevention = the standard prophylaxis."},
/*148*/ {"q":"Left Ventricle enlarged in Hypertension due to:","o":["Hyperplasia","Increased Stroke volume","Atrophy","Hypertrophy"],"a":3,"e":"Systemic hypertension causes pressure overload on the left ventricle — the LV responds with concentric hypertrophy (increased wall thickness, predominantly due to parallel addition of sarcomeres). Hypertrophy is an adaptive response to increased afterload.<br><br>Take Notes: hypertension → LV concentric hypertrophy (pressure overload) | Volume overload (e.g., AR, MR) → eccentric hypertrophy (cavity dilation) | Hypertrophy = increased cell size (not number) | LV hypertrophy = HTN = concentric = pressure adaptation."},
/*149*/ {"q":"A patient Known smoker diagnosed case of Myxedema and DM with BP recorded as 170/110mmHg. Which drug to Give for Hypertension?","o":["Levothyroxine","Propranolol","Captopril","Methimazole"],"a":2,"e":"In a patient with myxoedema (hypothyroidism), DM, and hypertension, captopril (ACE inhibitor) is the preferred antihypertensive. Beta-blockers (propranolol) are relatively contraindicated in hypothyroidism (mask symptoms, worsen bradycardia) and DM (mask hypoglycaemia).<br><br>Take Notes: hypertension + myxoedema + DM → captopril (ACE inhibitor) preferred | Propranolol → avoid in hypothyroidism (worsens bradycardia) + DM (masks hypoglycaemia) | ACE inhibitors → also renoprotective in DM | Captopril = the safe antihypertensive in myxoedema + DM."},
/*150*/ {"q":"Justice on medical ethics is:","o":["Let patient decide about treatment","Equity in providing medical resources to all patients equally","Equity to staff working","Equity to Doctor working"],"a":1,"e":"Justice in medical ethics refers to fair and equitable distribution of healthcare resources and treatment — ensuring patients receive care based on need, not wealth, social status, or other unjust discriminators.<br><br>Take Notes: justice (medical ethics) → fair/equitable distribution of healthcare resources | Autonomy → patient right to decide | Beneficence → doing good | Non-maleficence → avoid harm | Justice = equity = fair resource distribution."}
,
/*151*/ {"q":"Most radiosensitive tumor is:","o":["Medulloblastoma","Brain stem glioma","Astrocytoma","Ependymoma"],"a":1,"e":"Medulloblastoma (primitive neuroectodermal tumour/PNET) is the most radiosensitive brain tumour — the standard treatment includes craniospinal irradiation after surgery. Gliomas are relatively radioresistant.<br><br>Take Notes: most radiosensitive brain tumour → medulloblastoma | Treatment → surgery + craniospinal RT + chemotherapy | Most common malignant brain tumour in children | Medulloblastoma = radiosensitive = posterior fossa childhood tumour."},
/*152*/ {"q":"In acute phase of stress what will rise?","o":["GH","Cortisol","Insulin","Glucagon"],"a":1,"e":"Cortisol is the primary hormone of the chronic stress response (HPA axis). In acute stress, both cortisol and adrenaline rise rapidly. Cortisol promotes gluconeogenesis, protein catabolism, and immunosuppression during stress.<br><br>Take Notes: acute stress → adrenaline (immediate) + cortisol (sustained HPA axis) | Cortisol → gluconeogenesis + anti-inflammatory + immunosuppression | Insulin → falls during stress (counter-regulatory) | Cortisol = the acute phase stress hormone = HPA axis."},
/*153*/ {"q":"Peritonitis due to infection contains which type of Fluid?","o":["Transudative","Serous","Exudative","Fibrinous"],"a":2,"e":"Peritonitis from infection produces exudative fluid — high protein, high WBCs (neutrophils), LDH elevated. Exudate results from increased vascular permeability from infection/inflammation (Light's criteria: protein >3g/dL or fluid:serum protein >0.5).<br><br>Take Notes: infectious peritonitis → exudative fluid (high protein + WBCs) | Transudative → low protein (portal HTN, heart failure, hypoalbuminaemia) | Exudate = infection/inflammation = increased vascular permeability | Exudate = peritonitis = the fluid type."},
/*154*/ {"q":"After how long HBA1C should be repeated to estimate long term control of blood sugar?","o":["6 Months","2 Months","4 Months","3 Months"],"a":3,"e":"HbA1c reflects average blood glucose over 2-3 months (RBC lifespan ~120 days). It should be repeated every 3 months in diabetic patients for optimal glycaemic monitoring and treatment adjustment.<br><br>Take Notes: HbA1c → every 3 months (reflects 2-3 months average glucose) | Target → <6.5% or <48 mmol/mol | RBC lifespan = 120 days = the basis for 3-month monitoring | 3 months = HbA1c repeat = optimal interval."},
/*155*/ {"q":"A thalassemia major boy required multiple transfusions. What Hb level should be present before every transfusion?","o":["8g/dL","9g/dL","10g/dL","11g/dL"],"a":1,"e":"In thalassaemia major, the transfusion threshold is typically maintained at Hb 9-10 g/dL (pre-transfusion) to suppress ineffective erythropoiesis, prevent bone marrow expansion, and reduce extramedullary haemopoiesis. Most protocols use 9-9.5 g/dL as the trigger.<br><br>Take Notes: thalassaemia major transfusion threshold → Hb 9 g/dL (pre-transfusion target) | High-transfusion regimen → keeps Hb 9-12 g/dL | Iron chelation needed → due to transfusional iron overload | 9 g/dL = thalassaemia major = the transfusion trigger."},
/*156*/ {"q":"Most common pattern of genetic disease:","o":["Multifactorial","Autosomal dominant","Autosomal Recessive","X link Recessive"],"a":0,"e":"Multifactorial (polygenic + environmental) inheritance is the most common pattern of genetic disease — responsible for common conditions like hypertension, diabetes mellitus, heart disease, schizophrenia, and congenital malformations.<br><br>Take Notes: most common genetic disease pattern → multifactorial (polygenic + environment) | Examples → HTN + DM + CAD + cleft palate + neural tube defects | Autosomal dominant → Huntington's + Marfan's | Multifactorial = most common = complex trait inheritance."},
/*157*/ {"q":"A lady with cervical cancer of 3.5 cm. Ipsilateral and lymph nodes are enlarged with suspected metastasis (dysplasia). The staging classification will be:","o":["T1N2M1","T2N1M1","T2N1M0","T1NOMO"],"a":2,"e":"Cervical cancer 3.5 cm invading parametrium = T2 (>4 cm or with parametrial invasion). Ipsilateral nodal involvement = N1. No distant metastasis = M0. Therefore staging = T2N1M0 = Stage IIIC1 (FIGO 2018) or Stage III by older staging.<br><br>Take Notes: cervical cancer staging → T2 (parametrial/beyond cervix) + N1 (ipsilateral nodes) + M0 | T2N1M0 = Stage IIIC1 (FIGO 2018) | N1 = regional lymph node metastasis | T2N1M0 = the cervical cancer staging for this presentation."},
/*158*/ {"q":"Rectum in pelvic region is identified by:","o":["Appendices epiplociae","Complete muscular coat ANS","Posterior to prostate","Forms medial wall of ischiorectal fossa"],"a":1,"e":"The rectum is identified by having a complete muscular coat (taeniae coli fuse into a complete longitudinal muscle layer at the rectosigmoid junction) — unlike the colon which has taeniae coli (incomplete longitudinal muscle). The rectum also lacks appendices epiploicae and haustrations.<br><br>Take Notes: rectum identifying features → complete muscular coat (no taeniae coli) + no appendices epiploicae + no haustra | Colon → taeniae coli + appendices epiploicae + haustra | Taeniae coli fuse at rectosigmoid junction | Complete muscle coat = rectum = the identifying feature."},
/*159*/ {"q":"Lymphatic Drainage of 4th degree Cervical Carcinoma:","o":["Internal Iliac lymph nodes","Para Aortic lymph nodes","Superficial inguinal lymph nodes","Deep Inguinal Lymph nodes"],"a":0,"e":"Cervical carcinoma drains primarily to the internal iliac lymph nodes (first echelon), then to obturator, external iliac, common iliac, and finally para-aortic nodes. Internal iliac nodes are the primary cervical cancer lymph drainage.<br><br>Take Notes: cervical cancer drainage → internal iliac nodes (first echelon) | Then → common iliac → para-aortic | Vulva → superficial inguinal (not cervix) | Internal iliac = cervical carcinoma = the first-echelon nodes."},
/*160*/ {"q":"Abducent nerve damage will cause:","o":["Loss of upward gaze and adduction","Loss of downward gaze and abduction","Loss of downward gaze and adduction","Loss of lateral gaze"],"a":3,"e":"CN VI (abducens nerve) supplies only the lateral rectus muscle. Its damage causes loss of lateral gaze (abduction) of the ipsilateral eye, resulting in convergent squint (esotropia).<br><br>Take Notes: CN VI palsy → loss of lateral gaze (abduction) → convergent squint | CN III palsy → loss of medial, upward, downward gaze + ptosis + mydriasis | CN IV palsy → loss of downward gaze when adducted | Abducens = lateral gaze = loss of abduction."},
/*161*/ {"q":"After RTA patient presents with loss of light touch and pressure in Lower Leg. No other sensory or motor loss. Surgeon orders MRI because suspecting damage of?","o":["Anterior spino thalamic tract","Lateral spino thalamic Tract","Fasciculus Cunearus","Fasciculus Gracilis"],"a":3,"e":"Loss of light touch and pressure (fine touch + vibration + proprioception) in the lower limb only with no motor or pain/temperature deficit = fasciculus gracilis (medial dorsal column, carrying lower limb proprioception + fine touch). Gracilis = lower limb; cuneatus = upper limb.<br><br>Take Notes: lower limb fine touch + proprioception loss → fasciculus gracilis (medial dorsal column) | Fasciculus cuneatus → upper limb (lateral dorsal column) | Spinothalamic → pain + temperature (not this picture) | Fasciculus gracilis = lower limb = the medial dorsal column."},
/*162*/ {"q":"Right Conus Artery supplies:","o":["Infundibulum","SA Node","AV Node","Atria"],"a":0,"e":"The conus artery (right) is the first branch of the RCA, supplying the infundibulum (conus arteriosus/right ventricular outflow tract). A well-developed right conus artery anastomoses with the left conus artery from the LAD, forming the Vieussens ring — a collateral pathway in anterior MI.<br><br>Take Notes: right conus artery (first RCA branch) → infundibulum/RVOT | Anastomoses with left conus (from LAD) → Vieussens ring collateral | SA node artery → RCA (60%) or LCX (40%) | Infundibulum = right conus artery = the first RCA branch supply."},
/*163*/ {"q":"Mandibulofacial dysostosis occurs due to defect in:","o":["1st and 2nd Branchial arch","1st Branchial arch","1st Branchial Cleft","2nd Branchial Cleft"],"a":0,"e":"Treacher Collins syndrome (mandibulofacial dysostosis) results from failure of development of the 1st and 2nd branchial arch derivatives — causing malar hypoplasia, mandibular hypoplasia, conductive hearing loss (ossicle anomalies), and down-slanting palpebral fissures.<br><br>Take Notes: Treacher Collins = mandibulofacial dysostosis → 1st + 2nd branchial arch defect | Features → malar + mandibular hypoplasia + hearing loss + down-slanting eyes | TCOF1 gene mutation | 1st and 2nd arch = Treacher Collins = mandibulofacial dysostosis."},
/*164*/ {"q":"False positive anti D result from which of following?","o":["ESR","Infection","Inflammation","Rouleaux formation"],"a":3,"e":"Rouleaux formation (RBC stacking due to elevated fibrinogen/immunoglobulins in inflammation, infection, or multiple myeloma) can cause false positive results in ABO/RhD grouping tests by mimicking agglutination. This is a key pre-analytical error in blood banking.<br><br>Take Notes: false positive anti-D → rouleaux formation (stacked RBCs mimicking agglutination) | Caused by → elevated fibrinogen + paraprotein + inflammatory states | Saline replacement test → breaks up rouleaux | Rouleaux = false positive blood grouping = stacked RBCs."},
/*165*/ {"q":"Sympathetic nerves are located in which part of Spinal Cord?","o":["Lateral horn","Posterior horn","Gray matter","Anterior horn"],"a":0,"e":"Sympathetic preganglionic neurons are located in the lateral horn (intermediolateral cell column) of the spinal cord, at levels T1-L2 (thoracolumbar outflow). Parasympathetic preganglionic neurons are in the brainstem nuclei and sacral lateral horn (S2-S4).<br><br>Take Notes: sympathetic preganglionic → lateral horn (T1-L2) | Parasympathetic → brainstem nuclei + S2-S4 lateral horn | Somatic motor → anterior horn (alpha motor neurons) | Lateral horn = sympathetic = the thoracolumbar location."},
/*166*/ {"q":"A female with breast Carcinoma. His mother died of cervical carcinoma. Which of the following is not an oncogene in Breast Carcinoma?","o":["BRCA","APC","P53","HER2"],"a":1,"e":"APC (adenomatous polyposis coli) is a tumour suppressor gene for colorectal cancer — it is NOT an oncogene and is NOT associated with breast carcinoma. BRCA1/2, TP53, and HER2 are all associated with breast cancer (though BRCA/TP53 are tumour suppressors, not oncogenes).<br><br>Take Notes: breast cancer genes → BRCA1/2 (tumour suppressor) + HER2 (oncogene) + TP53 | APC → colorectal cancer (FAP) — not breast cancer | APC = NOT a breast cancer oncogene = the odd one out | APC = colorectal = not breast cancer."},
/*167*/ {"q":"Proximal part of CBD is supplied by:","o":["Inf mesenteric artery","Sup mesenteric artery","Cystic artery","Right hepatic artery"],"a":3,"e":"The proximal common bile duct is supplied by the right hepatic artery (via cystic duct artery and retroduodenal artery branches). The distal CBD is supplied by the gastroduodenal artery. This vascular supply is critical in biliary surgery.<br><br>Take Notes: proximal CBD → right hepatic artery branches | Distal CBD → gastroduodenal artery | Ischaemic stricture → from right hepatic artery injury during cholecystectomy | Right hepatic artery = proximal CBD = the bile duct blood supply."},
/*168*/ {"q":"A boy presenter with history of Fever on and off, Recurrent jaundice and Cola coloured urine. O/E Splenomegaly found. Investigations reveal Decreased HB. Possible Diagnosis:","o":["Immune Hemolytic Anemia","G6PD","Falciparum Malaria","Anemia of chronic disease"],"a":1,"e":"G6PD deficiency presents with recurrent episodes of haemolytic jaundice (cola-coloured urine = haemoglobinuria) triggered by infections, oxidant drugs, or foods. Splenomegaly develops from chronic haemolysis. On-off fever coincides with haemolytic episodes.<br><br>Take Notes: recurrent haemolysis + cola urine + splenomegaly + trigger episodes → G6PD deficiency | X-linked recessive | Triggers → infections + primaquine + dapsone + fava beans | G6PD = episodic haemolysis = the recurrent jaundice cause."},
/*169*/ {"q":"Increased Serum Ferritin and Decreased TIBC in:","o":["Iron deficiency Anemia","Anemia of Chronic disease","Thalassemia","Sideroblastic Anemia"],"a":1,"e":"Anaemia of chronic disease (ACD) shows increased ferritin (positive acute phase reactant) and decreased TIBC (iron sequestered in macrophages, less available for transport). Serum iron is also low, but unlike IDA, ferritin is elevated.<br><br>Take Notes: ACD → ↑ferritin + ↓TIBC + ↓serum iron | IDA → ↓ferritin + ↑TIBC + ↓serum iron | Ferritin ↑ = ACD (ferritin = acute phase reactant) | Ferritin high + TIBC low = chronic disease anaemia = the pattern."},
/*170*/ {"q":"Polychromasia in RBCs due to:","o":["Cytoplasmic RNA","Cytoplasmic DNA","Nuclear RNA","Microtubules & Filaments"],"a":0,"e":"Polychromasia (blue-red tinge of RBCs on Giemsa stain) is caused by residual cytoplasmic RNA in reticulocytes — newly released RBCs that retain ribosomes after nuclear extrusion. They appear polychromatic (bluish-pink) rather than fully eosinophilic.<br><br>Take Notes: polychromasia → residual cytoplasmic RNA in reticulocytes | Indicates → active erythropoiesis (haemolysis, blood loss) | Supravital stain → shows reticulocyte reticulum | Cytoplasmic RNA = polychromasia = reticulocyte marker."},
/*171*/ {"q":"Mechanism of action of aspirin in myocardial infarction is:","o":["Inhibition of thromboxane synthesis","Inhibition of cyclooxygenase enzyme","Inhibition of prostacyclin synthesis","Inhibition of formation of free radicals"],"a":0,"e":"Low-dose aspirin in MI acts by irreversibly inhibiting COX-1 in platelets, blocking thromboxane A2 (TXA2) synthesis — preventing platelet aggregation and vasoconstriction. This antiplatelet effect is the mechanism of cardioprotection.<br><br>Take Notes: aspirin in MI → inhibits TXA2 synthesis (COX-1 in platelets, irreversible) | TXA2 → promotes aggregation + vasoconstriction | PGI2 (prostacyclin) → also inhibited at high dose but platelet effect dominates | TXA2 inhibition = aspirin MI mechanism = antiplatelet."},
/*172*/ {"q":"The synovial sheath of the flexor pollicis longus muscle forms the:","o":["Thenar space","Radial bursa of the wrist","Midpalmar space","Ulnar Bursa of the wrist"],"a":1,"e":"The synovial sheath of flexor pollicis longus extends from above the wrist through the carpal tunnel to the thumb, forming the radial bursa. The ulnar bursa is formed by the common flexor sheath of the remaining fingers.<br><br>Take Notes: FPL synovial sheath → radial bursa (thumb side) | Common flexor sheath (FDS/FDP) → ulnar bursa | Communication → radial + ulnar bursae communicate in 50% | Radial bursa = FPL sheath = the thumb carpal tunnel synovial sheath."},
/*173*/ {"q":"While taking blood sample at cubital fossa which nerve is most likely to be injured?","o":["Median","Ulnar","Radial","Musculocutaneous"],"a":0,"e":"The median nerve is the most likely nerve to be injured during cubital fossa venepuncture — it lies medial to the brachial artery, which is the target vessel. The nerve is close enough to be inadvertently needled during blood sampling.<br><br>Take Notes: cubital fossa venepuncture → median nerve at risk (medial to brachial artery) | Cubital fossa order → median nerve, brachial artery, biceps tendon, radial nerve | Median nerve injury → thenar wasting + lateral 3.5 finger numbness | Median nerve = cubital fossa venepuncture risk."},
/*174*/ {"q":"Structure present between celiac trunk and superior mesenteric artery is?","o":["Pancreas","Stomach","Spleen","Duodenum"],"a":0,"e":"The neck and body of the pancreas lies between the coeliac trunk (origin T12/L1) and the superior mesenteric artery (origin L1). The SMA passes posterior to the neck of the pancreas, making the pancreatic neck the surgical landmark dividing the pancreas into head (right of SMA) and body/tail (left).<br><br>Take Notes: between coeliac trunk and SMA → pancreatic neck | SMA → passes posterior to pancreatic neck | Pancreatic neck division → head (right) + body/tail (left of SMA) | Pancreas = between coeliac + SMA = the pancreatic neck landmark."},
/*175*/ {"q":"During laparotomy which layer would surgeon encounter between Fat layer and transversus abdominis muscle?","o":["Skin","Subcutaneous layer (fatty layer)","Transversalis fascia","External oblique"],"a":2,"e":"The layers of the anterior abdominal wall from outside in: skin → subcutaneous fat (Camper's) → Scarpa's fascia → external oblique → internal oblique → transversus abdominis → transversalis fascia → extraperitoneal fat → peritoneum. Between the fat (subcutaneous) and transversus abdominis lies the transversalis fascia (after the muscle layers).<br><br>Take Notes: abdominal wall layers → skin → Camper's fat → Scarpa's → EO → IO → TA → transversalis fascia → peritoneum | Transversalis fascia = immediately deep to TA | Between fat layer and TA → muscle layers (EO + IO) | Transversalis fascia = deepest musculofascial layer = just deep to TA."},
/*176*/ {"q":"Foramen which opens into infratemporal fossa:","o":["Foramen Lacerum","Foramen Cecum","Stylomastoid Foramen","Sphenopalatine Foramen"],"a":3,"e":"The sphenopalatine foramen (between the perpendicular plate of the palatine bone and the body of the sphenoid) opens medially into the nasal cavity and laterally communicates with the pterygopalatine fossa, which connects to the infratemporal fossa via the pterygomaxillary fissure.<br><br>Take Notes: sphenopalatine foramen → connects nasal cavity to pterygopalatine fossa | Pterygopalatine fossa → connects to infratemporal fossa (pterygomaxillary fissure) | Foramen ovale → mandibular nerve to infratemporal fossa | Sphenopalatine = nasal cavity = pterygopalatine fossa connection."},
/*177*/ {"q":"Mass Left to Midline in neck, diagnosed as a firm Cold nodule with normal adjacent surroundings and Thyroid function normal. Diagnosis:","o":["Thyroglossal Duct cyst","Papillary Carcinoma","Follicular Adenoma","Medullary Carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"A midline neck mass (between hyoid and thyroid) that moves on tongue protrusion and swallowing = thyroglossal duct cyst. It arises from remnants of the thyroglossal duct (path of thyroid descent from foramen caecum to neck). Normal thyroid function confirms it's not a thyroid mass.<br><br>Take Notes: midline neck cyst moving on tongue protrusion → thyroglossal duct cyst | From remnant of thyroglossal duct | Moves on swallowing + tongue protrusion (attached to hyoid) | Midline + moves with tongue = thyroglossal duct cyst."},
/*178*/ {"q":"Greater Sciatic foramen is traversed by which muscle?","o":["Obturator Internus","Piriformis","Obturator externus","Gluteus maximus"],"a":1,"e":"Piriformis is the primary muscle traversing the greater sciatic foramen, exiting the pelvis to insert into the greater trochanter. It is the key landmark dividing the foramen into supra-piriform and infra-piriform compartments.<br><br>Take Notes: greater sciatic foramen → piriformis exits (pelvis to greater trochanter) | Above piriformis → superior gluteal NVB | Below piriformis → sciatic nerve + inferior gluteal + pudendal | Piriformis = greater sciatic foramen = the reference muscle."},
/*179*/ {"q":"In metaplasia, if Spindles divide transversely rather than longitudinally. What will happen?","o":["Trisomy","Monosomy","Isochromosome","Aneuploidy"],"a":2,"e":"If the centromere divides transversely (rather than longitudinally), an isochromosome is formed — both arms of the resulting chromosomes are identical (either two short arms or two long arms). The classic example is isochromosome 17q in medulloblastoma and Turner syndrome (Xi(Xq)).<br><br>Take Notes: transverse centromere division → isochromosome (identical arms) | i(17q) → medulloblastoma | i(Xq) → Turner syndrome (45,X with isochromosome) | Isochromosome = transverse division = identical chromosome arms."},
/*180*/ {"q":"Which of the following poses Genetic predisposition to schizophrenia?","o":["Siblings","Monozygotic Twins","Dizygotic Twins","Children of Affected Mother and Father"],"a":3,"e":"The highest genetic risk for schizophrenia is in children of two affected parents (~46% risk) > monozygotic twins (~48% concordance) > dizygotic twins (~17%) > siblings (~9%). When both parents are affected, the offspring risk is highest in terms of genetic predisposition.<br><br>Take Notes: schizophrenia genetic risk (highest) → children of two affected parents | MZ twin concordance → ~48% (not 100%, so environment matters) | DZ twin → ~17% | Children of affected parents = highest genetic predisposition = schizophrenia."},
/*181*/ {"q":"Patient presents with pain in lumbar region. Stone at pelvic ureteric junction. Pain arising from which segment?","o":["T11-L1","L1-L4","T12-L2","L5"],"a":0,"e":"Ureteric colic from PUJ stones causes pain referred to T11-L1 dermatome — flank pain radiating to the groin and inner thigh. The ureter's pain fibres travel with sympathetic nerves entering at T11-L1 spinal levels.<br><br>Take Notes: ureteric pain → T11-L1 dermatome (flank to groin) | PUJ stone → most common ureteric stone site | VUJ stone → pain to tip of penis/labia | T11-L1 = ureteric colic = the spinal segment."},
/*182*/ {"q":"A Lady who is always crying and sometimes have uncontrolled laugh. She is socially isolated, depressed and has recurrent mood changes. Defect lies in:","o":["Left Frontal Cortex","Right Frontal Cortex","Cingulate gyrus","Amygdala"],"a":3,"e":"Emotional lability (uncontrolled laughing and crying), social isolation, and recurrent mood changes suggest a limbic system dysfunction. The amygdala regulates emotional responses — bilateral amygdala damage or dysfunction causes emotional dysregulation, inappropriate emotional responses, and social difficulties (Klüver-Bucy components).<br><br>Take Notes: emotional lability + social isolation + mood changes → amygdala dysfunction | Amygdala → fear + anger + social behaviour + emotional memory | Orbitofrontal cortex → social judgement | Amygdala = emotional dysregulation = the limbic defect."},
/*183*/ {"q":"Valve involved in interventricular septal defect:","o":["Aortic","Mitral","Tricuspid","Pulmonary"],"a":2,"e":"In VSD, the tricuspid valve is closely related to the perimembranous ventricular septal defect (the most common type, ~80% of VSDs). The septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve is adjacent to the membranous septum, and VSD closure must avoid damage to this leaflet and the nearby aortic valve.<br><br>Take Notes: VSD (perimembranous) → adjacent to tricuspid valve septal leaflet | Aortic valve → also close to membranous VSD | Tricuspid = the valve most involved in perimembranous VSD | Tricuspid = VSD = the adjacent valve."},
/*184*/ {"q":"Most common cerebellar tumor in Children?","o":["GBM","Meningioma","Medulloblastoma","Ependymoma"],"a":2,"e":"Medulloblastoma (PNET) is the most common malignant brain tumour in children and the most common cerebellar tumour in children. It arises from the cerebellar vermis, causing truncal ataxia, and spreads via CSF (drop metastases).<br><br>Take Notes: most common cerebellar tumour in children → medulloblastoma | Arises from cerebellar vermis | CSF spread → drop metastases to spinal cord | Medulloblastoma = children + cerebellum = most common malignant paediatric brain tumour."},
/*185*/ {"q":"Patient had a stroke followed by loss of appetite and thirst and was throwing things around. Loss of thirst is due to increase in?","o":["Vasopressin","Stimulation of Lateral hypothalamus","Angiotensin 2","Stimulation of Medial hypothalamus"],"a":1,"e":"The lateral hypothalamus contains the thirst centre and hunger centre. Stimulation (or irritation from stroke) of the lateral hypothalamus increases thirst and hunger — loss of thirst after stroke suggests lateral hypothalamic damage, where stimulation would normally promote drinking.<br><br>Take Notes: thirst centre → lateral hypothalamus | Satiety centre → ventromedial hypothalamus | Lateral hypothalamus damage → loss of hunger + thirst | Stimulation of lateral hypothalamus = increased thirst = the drinking drive centre."},
/*186*/ {"q":"Sodium reabsorption is a function of:","o":["ANP","Aldosterone","Cortisol","ADH"],"a":1,"e":"Aldosterone (from adrenal cortex zona glomerulosa) is the primary hormone controlling sodium reabsorption — it acts on principal cells of the collecting duct, upregulating ENaC (epithelial sodium channels) and Na+/K+-ATPase, increasing Na+ reabsorption and K+ secretion.<br><br>Take Notes: Na+ reabsorption → aldosterone (collecting duct, ENaC) | ANP → promotes Na+ excretion (opposes aldosterone) | ADH → water reabsorption (not Na+) | Aldosterone = Na+ reabsorption = the primary sodium-conserving hormone."},
/*187*/ {"q":"Superior pancreaticoduodenal artery is a branch of:","o":["Short gastric artery","Gastroduodenal artery","Splenic artery","Left Gastric artery"],"a":1,"e":"The superior pancreaticoduodenal artery (anterior and posterior divisions) is a branch of the gastroduodenal artery (GDA), which arises from the common hepatic artery (coeliac axis). It supplies the proximal duodenum and head of pancreas.<br><br>Take Notes: superior pancreaticoduodenal → from GDA → from common hepatic → from coeliac | Inferior pancreaticoduodenal → from SMA | They anastomose → watershed between coeliac + SMA | GDA = superior pancreaticoduodenal = the coeliac territory supply."},
/*188*/ {"q":"Earliest of all, indicator of low calcium level in the body is:","o":["Ca+ level","Tetany","Chronic renal failure","25 Vitamin D3 level"],"a":1,"e":"Tetany (carpopedal spasm, Chvostek's sign, Trousseau's sign) is the earliest clinical indicator of hypocalcaemia — the increased neuromuscular excitability from low ionised calcium produces muscle spasm before other features (seizures, cardiac arrhythmias) develop.<br><br>Take Notes: earliest hypocalcaemia sign → tetany (neuromuscular excitability) | Chvostek's sign → facial muscle twitch on tapping facial nerve | Trousseau's sign → carpal spasm with BP cuff inflation | Tetany = hypocalcaemia = the earliest clinical indicator."},
/*189*/ {"q":"Patient with Myxedema will present with:","o":["Weight loss","Heat Intolerance","Protein loss","Increased Lipolysis"],"a":2,"e":"Myxoedema (severe hypothyroidism) causes protein loss through reduced protein synthesis and catchy interstitial accumulation of glycosaminoglycans. Other features: weight gain, cold intolerance, bradycardia, and reduced BMR — not weight loss or heat intolerance.<br><br>Take Notes: myxoedema (hypothyroidism) → weight gain + cold intolerance + bradycardia + constipation | Glycosaminoglycan accumulation → non-pitting oedema (myxoedema) | Protein synthesis reduced → protein loss | Myxoedema = hypothyroidism = weight gain NOT loss."},
/*190*/ {"q":"Which of the following is NOT a feature of nephrotic syndrome?","o":["Massive proteinuria","Hypoalbuminaemia","Haematuria","Hyperlipidaemia"],"a":2,"e":"Nephrotic syndrome is defined by: massive proteinuria (>3.5g/day), hypoalbuminaemia, generalised oedema, and hyperlipidaemia/lipiduria. Haematuria is a feature of NEPHRITIC syndrome (glomerulonephritis with inflammation), not nephrotic syndrome.<br><br>Take Notes: nephrotic syndrome → proteinuria + hypoalbuminaemia + oedema + hyperlipidaemia | Haematuria → nephritic syndrome (inflammatory, e.g., IgA nephropathy, post-strep GN) | 'Otic = protein out' | Haematuria = nephritic NOT nephrotic = the absent feature."}
];
